10:51.151 --> 10:53.111
What seems to be the problem?

10:53.195 --> 10:55.030
I’m sorry you’re having
technical difficulties.

10:55.113 --> 10:57.115
I’m sorry you’re
having technical difficulties.

10:57.199 --> 10:58.867
-I’m sorry you’re having...
-I’m sorry you’re having...

10:58.950 --> 11:00.660
I’m sorry you’re having
technical difficulties.

11:00.744 --> 11:02.329
-What seems to be the problem?
-I’m sorry you’re having...

11:02.412 --> 11:04.373
I’m sorry you’re having
technical difficulties.

11:04.456 --> 11:06.291
-[siren wailing]
-[traffic passing]

11:06.375 --> 11:08.460
-[construction vehicle beeping]
-[dog barking]

11:08.543 --> 11:10.712
♪ ♪

11:27.479 --> 11:29.648
[horns honking]

11:34.069 --> 11:36.363
[laughter, lively chatter]

11:38.865 --> 11:40.242
Can I get a whiskey?

11:40.325 --> 11:41.618
Double.

11:41.701 --> 11:44.037
-No ice.
-You got it, Greggo.

11:56.591 --> 11:58.593
Be right back.

12:15.152 --> 12:17.529
[panting]

12:19.072 --> 12:21.825
-I’ll start you a tab.
-Great.

12:38.091 --> 12:39.885
[muffled thump]

12:41.261 --> 12:42.971
-[muffled thump]
-[light crackles]

12:44.139 --> 12:45.724
[muffled thumping]

12:48.560 --> 12:49.769
You’re real.

12:51.021 --> 12:52.022
Sorry?

12:52.105 --> 12:54.816
You know you’re real, right?

12:54.900 --> 12:58.361
I was just waiting for...
I’m sorry, do I know you?

12:58.445 --> 13:00.280
You deflected my powers.

13:00.363 --> 13:01.323
I’m sorry?

13:01.406 --> 13:02.449
Stop apologizing.

13:02.532 --> 13:03.825
I’m not apologizing.

13:03.909 --> 13:05.410
I don’t hear you.

13:05.494 --> 13:07.662
I can’t understand
what you’re saying.

13:17.756 --> 13:19.299
[soft whoosh]

13:19.382 --> 13:21.510
[items clattering]

13:27.849 --> 13:30.185
I don’t recognize you.

13:30.268 --> 13:31.770
I-I-I don’t know you.

13:32.938 --> 13:34.898
It’s always blurry at first.

13:34.981 --> 13:36.483
I’m Isabel.

13:36.566 --> 13:37.859
Come sit with me.

13:37.943 --> 13:39.236
I’m-I’m fine.

13:39.319 --> 13:42.405
I’m just gonna have my drink.
Thank you.

13:42.489 --> 13:46.034
You need an alibi, don’t you?

13:50.539 --> 13:52.457
What?

13:58.129 --> 14:00.298
Interesting view.

14:06.096 --> 14:09.808
Your next step is
extremely important.

14:09.891 --> 14:12.727
You do not want to spend
this life in prison.

14:12.811 --> 14:15.730
That would be very, very bad.

14:16.356 --> 14:17.274
Look at me.

14:17.357 --> 14:19.276
I am going to help you because,

14:19.359 --> 14:22.571
personally, I feel a little bit
responsible for your situation.

14:22.654 --> 14:24.447
Why do you feel responsible?

14:24.531 --> 14:27.701
Let’s just say it’s kind of
my fault this world exists.

14:27.784 --> 14:29.828
[indistinct chanting outside]

14:29.911 --> 14:31.162
[Isabel]
Don’t worry about it.

14:31.246 --> 14:33.373
It’s gonna be okay.
I’m gonna fix it.

14:33.456 --> 14:35.584
But first, you need to do
something for me.

14:35.667 --> 14:38.003
I have a boyfriend-- an ex.

14:39.504 --> 14:42.674
He’s a real asshole,
and he’s in the bathroom.

14:42.757 --> 14:43.967
Okay.

14:44.050 --> 14:45.760
[Isabel] He has something
that belongs to me.

14:45.844 --> 14:47.887
Are you even listening to me?

14:47.971 --> 14:49.014
Yes.

14:49.097 --> 14:51.349
-About your boyfriend.
-Ex.

14:51.433 --> 14:54.936
He has my amulet necklace,
and I need it back.

14:55.020 --> 14:57.397
Why can’t you use your powers
on your boyfriend?

14:57.480 --> 14:59.608
Because he’s real,
like you and I.

14:59.691 --> 15:02.193
You keep saying "real."
What do you mean by "real"?

15:04.529 --> 15:06.615
You see all these people
outside?

15:06.698 --> 15:08.158
They’re not real.

15:08.241 --> 15:11.077
The bartender-- not real.

15:11.161 --> 15:13.413
Nothing, nothing,
nothing of this is real.

15:13.496 --> 15:15.498
There’s very few of us.

15:15.582 --> 15:17.250
I think you need help.

15:17.334 --> 15:20.295
No, you need help.

15:20.378 --> 15:22.005
Get me my necklace,

15:22.088 --> 15:24.841
and I will fix
the problem for you, Greg.

15:24.924 --> 15:27.260
How do you know my name?

15:27.344 --> 15:29.929
[whispers]
I took it from your mind.

15:30.889 --> 15:32.265
[chuckles]
I’m just kidding.

15:32.349 --> 15:35.185
The bartender just said it
like a minute ago.

15:35.268 --> 15:36.686
Come on, Greg.

15:36.770 --> 15:39.481
What have you got to lose?

15:41.941 --> 15:45.278
[Greg] Why is this necklace
so important?

15:45.362 --> 15:49.074
[Isabel] It contains
special yellow crystals

15:49.157 --> 15:52.952
with the power
to manipulate this fake world.

16:06.883 --> 16:08.927
[Isabel sighs, kisses necklace]

16:10.095 --> 16:12.013
Well done. That was fast.

16:12.097 --> 16:13.848
Did he give you any trouble?

16:13.932 --> 16:15.558
No, he was just passed out.

16:15.642 --> 16:16.851
Really? Great.

16:16.935 --> 16:18.937
Get back in there
and get the wallet.

16:19.020 --> 16:20.355
Drinks on him.

16:20.438 --> 16:22.232
No, I can... I got money.

16:22.315 --> 16:23.900
He owes me.

16:23.983 --> 16:26.277
♪ ♪

16:43.586 --> 16:44.838
[taps on table]

16:44.921 --> 16:47.632
Okay, guapo.

16:47.716 --> 16:49.676
Time to solve your problem.

16:53.054 --> 16:55.265
You deserve a clean break.

16:55.348 --> 16:56.599
Okay.

16:56.683 --> 16:58.601
I’m gonna fix it.

16:58.685 --> 17:00.854
♪ ♪

17:21.916 --> 17:23.877
Hey.

17:23.960 --> 17:25.920
You see this?

17:28.423 --> 17:34.179
The world is simply light
bouncing around your neurons.

17:34.262 --> 17:38.183
It’s manufactured and malleable.

17:38.266 --> 17:40.560
You’re free.

17:43.229 --> 17:45.523
♪ ♪

17:46.733 --> 17:49.027
-[glass squeaking]
-[phones ringing]

18:02.332 --> 18:05.043
[people screaming, gasping]

18:11.925 --> 18:13.468
[man]
He jumped!

18:13.551 --> 18:14.969
-He jumped! He jumped!
-No.

18:15.053 --> 18:16.930
He jumped out of the window!
Right there.

18:17.013 --> 18:18.890
He just fucking
committed suicide

18:18.973 --> 18:21.017
-in the middle of the day!
-What?

18:21.100 --> 18:22.644
What were you doing in the bar?

18:22.727 --> 18:24.103
Nothing.
I was just getting a snack.

18:24.187 --> 18:26.272
-I was just...
-Let’s go.

18:27.607 --> 18:29.901
-Did you do that?
-Did what?

18:29.984 --> 18:32.153
A dozen witnesses saw him
jump out of the window,

18:32.237 --> 18:34.948
and then saw you walk out
of the bar across the street.

18:35.031 --> 18:37.700
-[tires screech, horn honks]
-Convinced yet?

18:40.286 --> 18:41.996
-[Greg] I forgot my wallet.
-[sirens approaching]

18:42.080 --> 18:44.040
-Forget about it.
-No, no, I can go back.

18:44.123 --> 18:46.042
-I’m innocent, right?
-You can’t go back.

18:46.125 --> 18:48.878
You have to lay low for a while
till the case closes.

18:48.962 --> 18:50.296
But you said yourself that

18:50.380 --> 18:52.090
they saw me at the bar--
the witnesses.

18:52.173 --> 18:53.800
-Exactly.
-[siren wailing, horn honking]

18:53.883 --> 18:55.426
Let them do the talking.

18:55.510 --> 18:57.762
Last thing you need is
to be in a dark room,

18:57.846 --> 19:01.641
bright light on your face,
with the Five-O tripping you up,

19:01.724 --> 19:04.769
because you will
for sure fuck it up.

19:04.853 --> 19:06.688
Just lay low.

19:06.771 --> 19:08.439
You have a phone?

19:08.523 --> 19:09.816
Yeah. Why?

19:09.899 --> 19:11.442
[reporter] ...inequality
of income and wealth

19:11.526 --> 19:14.237
has surged in recent years.
Protestors are...

19:14.320 --> 19:16.406
We’ll use science
to shape policy.

19:16.489 --> 19:18.575
[reporter 2]
Not everyone is convinced.

19:18.658 --> 19:19.951
It doesn’t make any sense.

19:20.034 --> 19:21.411
Bjorn was happy.

19:21.494 --> 19:23.913
He wasn’t depressed.

19:23.997 --> 19:25.373
It’s not possible.

19:25.456 --> 19:27.709
The most likely cause of death
is suicide,

19:27.792 --> 19:31.129
although police have not
ruled out foul play.

19:31.212 --> 19:32.881
Yo. Phone.

19:32.964 --> 19:34.883
[indistinct, overlapping
broadcasts continue]

19:38.636 --> 19:41.097
[Greg on video]
Hi. I’m Dad, and this is...

19:41.180 --> 19:42.265
[Young Emily]
Emily.

19:42.348 --> 19:44.559
[Greg]
And who’s the one on your shirt?

19:44.642 --> 19:47.896
This is... Turtleistic.

19:47.979 --> 19:49.981
[Greg laughing]
That’s perfect.

19:50.064 --> 19:51.608
-That’s great.
-[Emily] Turtleistic.

19:51.691 --> 19:53.109
-Cute.
-[Greg on video] Turtleistic.

19:53.192 --> 19:54.611
-[drops phone on table]
-How much for this?

19:54.694 --> 19:57.071
-I’ll give you 60 bucks.
-Done.

19:57.155 --> 19:58.156
ID.

19:58.239 --> 19:59.824
I don’t have a wallet.

19:59.908 --> 20:01.826
I... Can you use yours?

20:01.910 --> 20:03.161
Can she use hers?

20:03.244 --> 20:04.704
[Isabel]
40.

20:07.749 --> 20:08.791
Ten.

20:10.919 --> 20:13.338
[Isabel] I mean, better than
tossing it on the trash can.

20:13.421 --> 20:15.506
[Greg] Oh, for sure,
but they just grind you

20:15.590 --> 20:17.383
on that no-ID thing.

20:17.467 --> 20:19.135
-Did you know that?
-No.

20:19.218 --> 20:22.472
I don’t have a phone.
I’m not that stupid.

20:22.555 --> 20:23.973
♪ ♪

20:31.898 --> 20:33.733
-Wh-Where are we going?
-We’re going here,

20:33.816 --> 20:36.527
where you’ll be safe
until the case closes.

20:46.454 --> 20:50.291
Welcome to my home
away from home.

20:51.626 --> 20:52.961
And this is my Ophelia.

20:53.044 --> 20:55.505
It’s okay, baby.

20:55.588 --> 20:58.091
[softly]
I can’t stay here.

20:58.174 --> 20:59.926
[louder]
Are you homeless?

21:01.094 --> 21:03.513
Is this legal or...

21:03.596 --> 21:05.890
You know, I really
appreciate your help.

21:05.974 --> 21:08.226
I’m sorry, I think I’m gonna go.

21:08.309 --> 21:09.936
And where are you going?

21:10.019 --> 21:11.521
I’m gonna go home.

21:11.604 --> 21:13.523
Well, I’m staying in a motel,

21:13.606 --> 21:15.108
so I’ll go back
to the motel room,

21:15.191 --> 21:17.068
but I don’t have the key
’cause that’s in my wallet,

21:17.151 --> 21:19.821
but I’ll just... Well, no,
’cause my ID’s there also

21:19.904 --> 21:21.864
and my money.

21:21.948 --> 21:24.033
So I don’t have my ID
or the money,

21:24.117 --> 21:25.743
but maybe they’ll remember me.

21:25.827 --> 21:27.620
Hopefully,
they’ll remember me and...

21:27.704 --> 21:30.790
Dude, you’re homeless.

21:32.709 --> 21:34.043
The reason why
I’m not going home

21:34.127 --> 21:35.962
is because
I’m recently divorced.

21:36.045 --> 21:39.507
Okay, then just stick around
until things cool off,

21:39.590 --> 21:41.509
and then you can go get
your wallet,

21:41.592 --> 21:43.469
get yourself a house
or a new wife,

21:43.553 --> 21:45.096
whatever it is
that you want to do.

21:45.179 --> 21:46.681
I do have a television.

21:46.764 --> 21:48.725
You can watch the news there
on mute.

21:48.808 --> 21:52.145
-You have electricity?
-Yeah, and water.

21:52.228 --> 21:55.398
See, I’m not homeless,
just off the grid.

21:57.025 --> 22:00.695
I am offering you
a safe place to hide out.

22:00.778 --> 22:02.238
Take it or leave it.

22:02.321 --> 22:04.115
Okay? I’m not gonna be begging.

22:04.198 --> 22:08.870
It’s not like I enjoy
your company or anything.

22:13.082 --> 22:15.376
[horns honking,
siren wailing in distance]

22:18.713 --> 22:21.174
[jet engine passing,
dog barking in distance]

22:28.347 --> 22:29.724
[TV muted]

22:29.807 --> 22:31.476
[Greg]
"No foul play"?

22:31.559 --> 22:33.478
Do you see what that says?

22:33.561 --> 22:34.562
-Yeah.
-Huh?

22:34.645 --> 22:36.481
You are officially free.

22:36.564 --> 22:38.900
Yes! [sighs]

22:41.235 --> 22:42.403
Well, I...

22:42.487 --> 22:44.989
Thank you. Thank you. I will...

22:45.865 --> 22:48.326
I will get out of your hair now.

22:48.409 --> 22:49.619
That’s it?

22:51.370 --> 22:53.956
So eager to walk out the door.

22:54.040 --> 22:56.334
No, no, I’m not. I...

22:57.210 --> 23:00.213
Are you cooking something?

23:00.296 --> 23:02.840
Just stir-fry. Nothing.

23:04.050 --> 23:05.843
Well, I like...

23:06.677 --> 23:08.471
Do you have any extra?

23:11.641 --> 23:13.184
[Isabel]
To your innocence.

23:13.267 --> 23:14.602
Innocence.

23:14.685 --> 23:17.021
[takes deep breath]

23:19.357 --> 23:21.859
I do feel bad about Bjorn.

23:22.985 --> 23:24.570
Of course you feel bad.

23:24.654 --> 23:27.949
Well, ’cause he was... you know,
he was not a horrible guy.

23:28.032 --> 23:31.119
He could be a... actually,
a pretty nice guy sometimes.

23:31.202 --> 23:34.080
He let us wear shorts
sometimes to work.

23:34.163 --> 23:36.207
You know, in-in the summertime.

23:36.290 --> 23:38.084
No, I understand. I mean...

23:38.167 --> 23:39.752
I understand how you must feel.

23:39.836 --> 23:43.923
You killed a nice guy
that let you wear the shorts.

23:44.006 --> 23:46.801
And you think it’s real.

23:47.885 --> 23:50.513
But you know what?

23:50.596 --> 23:56.060
You just have to observe
the feeling and then let it go.

23:56.144 --> 23:58.771
I want to show you something
really cool.

23:58.855 --> 24:00.606
Take this lighter.

24:00.690 --> 24:02.525
And you see those candles
over there?

24:02.608 --> 24:05.361
Wave it at the candles.

24:13.953 --> 24:16.122
Well done.

24:19.500 --> 24:21.335
Oh, it wasn’t that hard.

24:21.419 --> 24:24.672
Now try to do it
without the lighter.

24:30.928 --> 24:32.597
You like that?

24:32.680 --> 24:35.183
[chuckles] Are you kidding me?

24:40.104 --> 24:42.398
[Isabel]
Mm.

24:42.481 --> 24:44.358
Beautiful.

24:44.442 --> 24:45.860
Well, bravo.

24:45.943 --> 24:49.822
Now that you’ve created
such a fantastic atmosphere,

24:49.906 --> 24:51.115
shall we dine?

24:51.199 --> 24:53.534
Do tell me about
this dream home.

24:53.618 --> 24:56.287
It’s just this persistent
fantasy that I can’t shake

24:56.370 --> 25:00.166
where I’m always drawing this...

25:00.249 --> 25:02.293
little abode
that’s on a peninsula,

25:02.376 --> 25:06.672
and I completely get lost in it.

25:06.756 --> 25:08.424
Show it to me.

25:08.507 --> 25:10.051
You have the drawings?

25:13.763 --> 25:15.431
Let’s see.

25:23.105 --> 25:24.732
I’m impressed.

25:24.815 --> 25:26.484
It’s very precise.

25:26.567 --> 25:28.236
Well, that’s the thing.

25:28.319 --> 25:30.947
It’s easy for me
to do the detail,

25:31.030 --> 25:32.823
’cause I see it
so clearly in my mind.

25:32.907 --> 25:34.700
Right there’s the path

25:34.784 --> 25:36.869
that leads out to just
sort of like a little room

25:36.953 --> 25:39.705
that just has a great view
of these mountains here.

25:39.789 --> 25:41.374
You love the pool.

25:41.457 --> 25:43.459
Yeah, that’s part
of an old ruin.

25:43.542 --> 25:46.212
And can you see
the hotel right there?

25:46.295 --> 25:47.964
It has an observatory.

25:48.047 --> 25:49.840
The Hotel Pleiades.

25:49.924 --> 25:51.467
Pleiades.

25:51.550 --> 25:53.594
Yeah, that’s a cluster of stars.

25:53.678 --> 25:56.013
In my mind, it feels real.

25:56.097 --> 25:57.473
I can see it.

25:57.556 --> 26:00.268
Greg, where do you think
this is?

26:00.351 --> 26:01.978
Where is it?

26:02.061 --> 26:03.938
Well, it’s right in
the brain-powered mind

26:04.021 --> 26:06.190
of Greg Wittle.

26:10.861 --> 26:12.822
-[Isabel chuckles]
-[Greg] What?

26:12.905 --> 26:14.907
[Isabel]
And who’s this?

26:16.659 --> 26:19.620
Kind of forgot
that one was in there.

26:22.957 --> 26:25.293
That is me.

26:25.376 --> 26:27.420
Look at her face.

26:27.503 --> 26:29.213
You drew me.

26:29.297 --> 26:32.758
Greg, this is not a fantasy.

26:32.842 --> 26:36.762
This is our real life,
outside of here.

26:36.846 --> 26:38.431
No, come on.

26:38.514 --> 26:40.224
How can that be...

26:40.308 --> 26:41.767
[stammering]
But you know that...

26:41.851 --> 26:43.477
-Shh.
-How... Did you...

26:43.561 --> 26:46.314
Let it be bigger
than your comprehension.

26:46.397 --> 26:49.108
You’re my guy.

26:49.191 --> 26:51.152
[waves lapping]

26:51.235 --> 26:52.737
I’m your guy?

26:52.820 --> 26:54.780
[birds chirping]

26:54.864 --> 26:57.033
You’re my guy.

27:02.288 --> 27:04.540
Kiss me.

27:26.270 --> 27:28.064
[rap music playing quietly]

27:29.190 --> 27:30.608
[Arthur sighs]

27:30.691 --> 27:32.401
So, what, your phone
doesn’t work anymore?

27:32.485 --> 27:35.404
Well, I knew
you’d try to avoid me.

27:37.198 --> 27:39.950
We need to talk about Dad.

27:40.034 --> 27:41.786
I-I need your help.

27:41.869 --> 27:43.162
I-I want to find him.

27:43.245 --> 27:44.914
I want him to come
to my graduation.

27:47.124 --> 27:49.335
Just let it go, Emmy, okay?

27:49.418 --> 27:51.670
Follow Mom’s lead.

27:51.754 --> 27:53.339
No.

27:53.422 --> 27:56.258
I think it’d be good for him.

27:56.342 --> 27:58.594
Think it’d be good
for all of us.

28:02.473 --> 28:04.892
[scoffs]

28:04.975 --> 28:09.105
Did he not bring your ass to,
like, every baseball practice?

28:09.188 --> 28:11.023
I hated baseball.

28:12.733 --> 28:14.068
-[taps table]
-[sighs]

28:14.151 --> 28:16.404
[rap music continues quietly]

28:26.414 --> 28:28.541
Who taught you
how to skateboard?

28:28.624 --> 28:30.501
He did.

28:32.336 --> 28:34.422
I remember.

28:35.297 --> 28:36.632
I remember how many times

28:36.715 --> 28:38.467
he busted his ass
trying to teach me shit

28:38.551 --> 28:40.136
-and trying to impress me.
-[laughing]

28:40.219 --> 28:41.720
I mean, I busted my ass, too,

28:41.804 --> 28:44.181
but he ate shit
way more than a few times.

28:49.937 --> 28:52.648
So, can you just, like...

28:52.731 --> 28:55.484
hold on to that?

28:55.568 --> 28:57.486
Help me find him.

29:00.990 --> 29:03.284
I can’t.

29:03.367 --> 29:04.493
Sorry.

29:04.577 --> 29:07.746
I just can’t trust him anymore.

29:16.213 --> 29:18.716
"Hey, Dad, how’s your back?"

29:18.799 --> 29:21.260
"It’s okay. It’s actually
my knee that’s bothering me."

29:21.343 --> 29:23.345
"Really? ’Cause I thought
you fixed that already."

29:23.429 --> 29:27.808
-"Oh, no. You must be thinking
about my shoulder." -Stop that.

29:27.892 --> 29:29.810
"Okay, your shoulder. Is it the
left one or the right one, Dad?

29:29.894 --> 29:32.146
-"What about next week? Is your
ankle gonna go?" -Stop it.

29:32.229 --> 29:34.982
-"Well, it’s always something
with you, Dad." -Stop it!

29:36.066 --> 29:39.028
[door opens, closes]

29:39.111 --> 29:42.448
["You and I" by Will Bates
featuring Skye Edwards playing]

29:43.282 --> 29:45.868
♪ Good ♪

29:45.951 --> 29:49.788
♪ Things ♪

29:49.872 --> 29:51.999
♪ Go ♪

29:53.626 --> 29:55.252
♪ Fast ♪

29:56.754 --> 29:58.172
Mm-mm.

29:58.255 --> 30:02.426
♪ The color’s draining out ♪

30:02.510 --> 30:08.682
♪ And it feels as if the fun ♪

30:08.766 --> 30:12.394
♪ Sweeps away ♪

30:12.478 --> 30:15.731
♪ The shame ♪

30:15.814 --> 30:21.362
♪ Of looking
through these eyes ♪

30:22.821 --> 30:28.744
♪ A harsh, bright
morning light ♪

30:28.827 --> 30:32.665
-♪ This town could be on fire ♪
-[man laughing]

30:32.748 --> 30:34.458
Douchebag!

30:35.918 --> 30:39.421
-♪ Far from the sky ♪
-[man speaking excitedly]

30:39.505 --> 30:41.882
-[soft whoosh]
-[grunts]

30:41.966 --> 30:48.264
♪ But you and I ♪

30:48.347 --> 30:53.561
♪ Can run to something else... ♪

30:53.644 --> 30:56.188
-Hey! Creep.
-Nice.

30:56.272 --> 30:57.982
[grunts] Down!

30:58.899 --> 31:00.192
[woman laughing]

31:00.276 --> 31:03.070
[mock whining]

31:03.153 --> 31:08.284
♪ It’s you and I ♪

31:08.367 --> 31:11.370
♪ That’s left ♪

31:11.453 --> 31:18.419
♪ Alone in this... ♪

31:18.502 --> 31:22.006
[Isabel]
Judgmental bitch. Take her down.

31:22.923 --> 31:25.050
What?

31:25.134 --> 31:26.552
Do it.

31:26.635 --> 31:29.263
-No.
-She’s not real.

31:29.346 --> 31:32.099
Get her.

31:32.182 --> 31:36.061
-[soft whooshing]
-[grunting]

31:39.023 --> 31:40.232
-Go!
-[rapid whooshing]

31:40.316 --> 31:42.318
[grunting]

31:42.401 --> 31:43.527
Yeah!

31:43.611 --> 31:46.989
♪ In the dark ♪

31:48.449 --> 31:54.371
♪ And it feels as if the fun ♪

31:54.455 --> 31:55.914
♪ Sweeps away... ♪

31:55.998 --> 31:58.167
[man]
Whoa. Whoa! Whoa, whoa!

31:58.250 --> 32:00.252
Oh, whoa! Watch out! [screams]

32:00.336 --> 32:01.629
[laughing]

32:01.712 --> 32:06.717
♪ Of looking
through these eyes... ♪

32:08.594 --> 32:11.096
I don’t have to feel guilty
about Bjorn!

32:11.180 --> 32:14.058
Cut through those illusions!

32:14.141 --> 32:20.522
♪ This town could be on fire ♪

32:21.857 --> 32:26.862
♪ Far from the sky ♪

32:27.946 --> 32:32.034
♪ But you and I ♪

32:32.117 --> 32:34.161
[both laughing]

32:34.244 --> 32:38.499
-♪ Will run behind the light ♪
-[train horn blaring]

32:38.582 --> 32:41.085
Oh. Stop!

32:41.168 --> 32:46.465
♪ With all we left behind ♪

32:48.592 --> 32:50.886
-♪ It’s you ♪
-[siren whoops]

32:50.969 --> 32:54.098
♪ And I ♪

32:54.181 --> 32:57.434
♪ That’s left ♪

32:57.518 --> 33:03.440
♪ Alone in this. ♪

33:18.580 --> 33:20.124
♪ ♪

33:32.678 --> 33:34.972
[indistinct
police radio chatter]

33:39.727 --> 33:41.478
[camera clicking]

33:44.231 --> 33:45.899
[officer]
There you go.

33:51.864 --> 33:53.407
Isabel. Hey.

33:53.490 --> 33:55.617
Ask me if I gave them my name.

33:55.701 --> 33:57.119
-Mm.
-Ask me.

33:57.202 --> 33:58.996
-Did you give them your name?
-No!

33:59.079 --> 34:00.789
-No way! Come on!
-No!

34:00.873 --> 34:02.624
I didn’t give them
your name, either.

34:02.708 --> 34:04.126
They can’t fuck with you

34:04.209 --> 34:06.712
-if you have no name, right?
-They don’t need it.

34:06.795 --> 34:09.006
[Isabel chuckling]

34:23.395 --> 34:24.521
You okay?

34:24.605 --> 34:26.482
I’m good.

34:26.565 --> 34:28.525
How do I seem?

34:30.068 --> 34:31.236
Good, right?

34:31.320 --> 34:32.446
Yeah.

34:32.529 --> 34:35.616
I’m a little disoriented,
but in a good way.

34:39.036 --> 34:40.829
Don’t worry about that.

34:40.913 --> 34:43.832
Hey, are you hungry?
Let’s go eat!

34:43.916 --> 34:45.584
-[Emily] Hi.
-[clerk] Hi.

34:45.667 --> 34:47.169
Have you seen my dad?

34:47.252 --> 34:48.879
That’s what he looks like.

34:48.962 --> 34:50.380
Haven’t seen him.

34:50.464 --> 34:53.217
I think he might have been
staying here a few weeks ago.

34:53.300 --> 34:55.052
No. Sorry.

34:55.135 --> 34:56.887
[woman in distance]
It’s your turn. Come on.

34:56.970 --> 34:58.972
-[man laughing]
-[man] Wait up. Yo.

34:59.056 --> 35:01.683
-Hey, yo, D.
-Yo.

35:01.767 --> 35:03.393
-Thank you.
-[laughter in distance]

35:05.354 --> 35:07.022
No, I don’t think so.

35:07.105 --> 35:11.193
Well, if you do see him,

35:11.276 --> 35:14.404
-will you please call me?
-Yeah.

35:14.488 --> 35:16.824
-Thank you so much.
-Yeah.

35:16.907 --> 35:18.867
We’re organizing a march.

35:18.951 --> 35:21.245
Situation’s gotten out of hand.
Come if you can.

35:22.412 --> 35:23.997
Yeah, I’ll be there.

35:31.797 --> 35:34.550
Get me a chicken sandwich
and some fries, okay?

35:34.633 --> 35:36.176
I’ll see you in there.
You go ahead.

35:36.260 --> 35:38.720
-And a soda?
-Yeah, and a soda.

35:38.804 --> 35:40.556
You got it.

35:49.648 --> 35:51.441
[employee]
Yo, what can I get for you?

35:51.525 --> 35:52.901
[Greg]
Can I get two

35:52.985 --> 35:54.611
artisanal chicken sandwiches,

35:54.695 --> 35:57.531
two large fries
and two sodas, please?

35:57.614 --> 35:59.700
That’ll be 12.76.

36:02.911 --> 36:05.497
Uh, okay,
my friend’s got my money.

36:05.581 --> 36:07.749
Let me just...

36:15.090 --> 36:17.426
I think I’m just gonna
go ahead and order later.

36:17.509 --> 36:19.678
Uh, all right.

36:19.761 --> 36:21.054
’Cause I want to get
everything together.

36:21.138 --> 36:22.639
Yeah, no problem.

36:24.725 --> 36:26.268
-It’s just easier.
-Yeah. No problem.

36:26.351 --> 36:27.978
[Greg]
I’ll just get it later.

36:31.023 --> 36:33.317
[indistinct chatter in distance]

36:38.906 --> 36:41.158
[people arguing in distance]

36:42.284 --> 36:44.620
[woman]
You want to go out, honey?

36:44.703 --> 36:45.996
I need money.

36:46.079 --> 36:48.498
-Come here, cutie.
-Hey, come here.

36:49.833 --> 36:52.169
-Did you hear what I said?
-[chatter continues]

36:53.670 --> 36:56.423
It’s expired,
but that don’t mean much.

36:56.506 --> 36:59.384
We have to toss food after
two hours on the shelf, so...

36:59.468 --> 37:01.970
-Okay, thanks.
-Yeah.

37:22.824 --> 37:26.078
It’s a little cold,
but it’s good.

37:26.161 --> 37:28.372
I don’t mind cold food.

37:51.603 --> 37:55.399
Let’s go find Kendo
and get the amulet refilled.

37:55.482 --> 37:57.985
♪ ♪

37:58.068 --> 38:00.904
[Greg] Well, that’s
the funny thing about accents is

38:00.988 --> 38:02.656
sometimes they can sound strong,

38:02.739 --> 38:04.533
depending on the region
that you’re in.

38:04.616 --> 38:06.910
But if you’re not from
that region, then it just...

38:06.994 --> 38:08.870
This is where you wait.

38:08.954 --> 38:10.706
I’ll be back.

38:10.789 --> 38:12.165
-Here?
-Yeah.

38:12.249 --> 38:14.001
Don’t move.

38:14.084 --> 38:16.128
[Greg wolf-whistles]

38:19.339 --> 38:21.091
♪ ♪

38:21.174 --> 38:22.384
[knocking]

38:27.472 --> 38:28.598
Hi, honey.

38:28.682 --> 38:29.933
[TV playing quietly]

38:30.017 --> 38:31.685
Who’s the new guy?

38:31.768 --> 38:33.729
Don’t want to talk about it.

38:33.812 --> 38:35.188
He’s cute.

38:35.272 --> 38:37.190
I’m here for some yellows.

38:37.274 --> 38:39.151
Fill it up.

38:39.234 --> 38:40.527
[sighs]

38:40.610 --> 38:43.155
You really broke my heart.
You know that.

38:43.238 --> 38:45.115
Get to work.

38:45.198 --> 38:46.658
I have real feelings.

38:50.078 --> 38:52.414
[man]
Hey, you want some mud? Junk?

38:52.497 --> 38:54.249
Skag?

38:54.332 --> 38:56.251
-Oh, no. No, no, I’m good.
-Black pearl?

38:56.334 --> 38:58.253
-Gato? Caballo?
-I’m all right.

38:58.336 --> 39:00.422
Hey, man, whatever. Your loss.

39:03.842 --> 39:06.470
-[electronic warbling]
-[TV continues quietly]

39:09.931 --> 39:11.266
[man on TV]
...instead of waiting around

39:11.349 --> 39:12.893
to collect
government handouts...

39:12.976 --> 39:14.770
[Emily] You sure he went
west on San Fernando?

39:14.853 --> 39:17.314
[Arthur] I-I-- No, I’m not sure.
I never said I was sure.

39:17.397 --> 39:19.775
I see him. Sir, can you just
pull over right here?

39:22.444 --> 39:24.321
And can you just wait
for one minute?

39:25.489 --> 39:27.032
-Dad?
-[car door closes]

39:27.115 --> 39:28.492
Dad.

39:29.868 --> 39:30.911
Emily?

39:30.994 --> 39:33.121
-[Emily] Hi.
-[Greg] Oh, my gosh.

39:33.205 --> 39:34.831
How are you?
What are you doing here?

39:34.915 --> 39:36.666
-I, um...
-Is everything okay?

39:36.750 --> 39:38.126
[sighs] Um...

39:38.210 --> 39:41.546
I’m sorry, it has been...
it’s been a crazy few days.

39:41.630 --> 39:44.591
I need you to come
with me right now.

39:44.674 --> 39:46.301
-Okay?
-Yes, of course.

39:46.384 --> 39:47.594
-Okay.
-Gosh, yes. Yeah, sure.

39:47.677 --> 39:49.012
-Okay, come on.
-No, but...

39:49.096 --> 39:50.722
[stammers]
Can we wait just a moment?

39:50.806 --> 39:52.933
I just...
I’m just waiting for...

39:53.016 --> 39:55.977
I’m waiting for someone,
for a friend.

39:56.061 --> 39:57.437
And then we’re gonna go.

39:57.521 --> 39:59.397
Dad.

39:59.481 --> 40:01.066
Please.

40:01.149 --> 40:02.526
[Isabel]
Hurry the fuck up, Kendo.

40:02.609 --> 40:04.820
I have to do this correctly.

40:04.903 --> 40:06.571
And I have places to be.

40:06.655 --> 40:08.156
Graduation.

40:08.240 --> 40:09.324
Oh, my God.

40:09.407 --> 40:10.826
I did not forget,

40:10.909 --> 40:12.410
and I’m definitely
gonna be there.

40:12.494 --> 40:16.998
And I want to take you
and Arthur to Cliff’s Edge

40:17.082 --> 40:19.417
with your mother,
if she’ll allow it.

40:19.501 --> 40:21.169
I already graduated, Dad.

40:23.171 --> 40:24.422
What?

40:24.506 --> 40:26.174
Like two weeks ago.

40:31.263 --> 40:32.764
It’s okay.

40:34.599 --> 40:36.059
It’s okay.

40:36.143 --> 40:37.686
Here, I-I’m gonna...

40:37.769 --> 40:38.895
[unzips bag]

40:38.979 --> 40:41.481
[rummaging]

40:41.565 --> 40:43.275
[quietly]
I have so many...

40:43.358 --> 40:44.818
...thoughts
I wish you could see.

40:44.901 --> 40:47.320
[Emily crying]
I’m gonna leave you with...

40:51.283 --> 40:53.577
Um, I’m gonna leave you
with this.

40:53.660 --> 40:55.203
It’s my phone number, okay?

40:55.287 --> 40:57.664
-Okay.
-Just call me when you’re ready.

41:05.213 --> 41:06.756
Is he real?

41:08.258 --> 41:10.051
Wouldn’t you like to know.

41:17.017 --> 41:19.227
[Isabel]
Who was that?

41:19.311 --> 41:21.521
Hey. Who was that?

41:25.692 --> 41:26.902
That’s my daughter.

41:26.985 --> 41:28.987
[scoffs]
Ignore her. She’s not real.

41:29.070 --> 41:31.198
-Why would you say that?
-Because it’s the truth.

41:31.281 --> 41:34.034
What do you want me to say?
I’m not making this shit up.

41:34.117 --> 41:38.121
Let’s just get off the street
and have some of this.

41:40.373 --> 41:42.292
Actually,
I don’t think I want any.

41:42.375 --> 41:45.295
I don’t think I want to have
any special powers right now.

41:45.378 --> 41:46.838
Fine, don’t.

41:46.922 --> 41:48.882
It’s not like anybody’s
twisting your arm or anything.

41:48.965 --> 41:50.675
No, I’m not saying
that you are...

41:50.759 --> 41:52.177
You think you can just walk

41:52.260 --> 41:54.179
through my neighborhood
tax-free?

41:58.683 --> 42:00.518
Oh.

42:00.602 --> 42:02.812
Don’t worry about me, huh?

42:02.896 --> 42:04.439
I’m fine.

42:04.522 --> 42:06.066
I don’t know about you, though.

42:06.149 --> 42:07.651
[man]
Don’t walk away from me.

42:09.069 --> 42:10.612
Isabel, come on.

42:10.695 --> 42:12.989
-Here, give me one of those.
-I thought you didn’t want any.

42:13.073 --> 42:15.367
Yeah, people make mistakes.
I made a mistake.

42:15.450 --> 42:16.910
Don’t make me beg.

42:16.993 --> 42:19.788
Isabel, please, come on.

42:22.165 --> 42:24.334
Hey, hey, that’s...

42:24.417 --> 42:25.961
That’s all we have.

42:26.044 --> 42:27.837
Give me that.

42:28.880 --> 42:31.716
[metallic creaking]

42:41.393 --> 42:43.520
[chuckling]
Oh, dude!

42:43.603 --> 42:44.771
Look at you.

42:44.854 --> 42:48.275
You’re like
the telekinetic warrior!

42:48.358 --> 42:50.652
[both grunting]

42:52.279 --> 42:54.030
[coughing, groaning]

42:54.114 --> 42:56.866
Okay, Greg.
Okay, it’s okay, it’s okay.

42:56.950 --> 42:59.577
[train passing nearby,
horn blows]

43:05.250 --> 43:07.419
[cat meowing]

43:16.803 --> 43:18.680
Isabel!

43:21.975 --> 43:23.935
Isabel.

43:27.272 --> 43:28.606
Isabel!

43:57.093 --> 43:59.262
♪ ♪

44:15.362 --> 44:17.155
Think fast, Greggo.

44:17.238 --> 44:18.531
Oh, yeah.

44:18.615 --> 44:20.241
Good on you, bud.

44:22.077 --> 44:24.287
[phone line ringing]

44:26.706 --> 44:29.042
[line ringing]

44:29.125 --> 44:31.169
[Emily recorded]
Hello. You’ve reached Emily.

44:31.252 --> 44:32.379
Leave me a message.

44:32.462 --> 44:35.465
Hey, it’s Dad, and, um,

44:35.548 --> 44:38.802
I am, um, just trying
to reach you.

44:38.885 --> 44:40.804
Um, you might not
recognize this number.

44:40.887 --> 44:42.514
I’m calling from a pay phone.

44:42.597 --> 44:44.808
But I will try you back.

44:44.891 --> 44:47.435
I don’t have my cell phone,
so I’ll try you back.

44:47.519 --> 44:49.437
All right, thank you.

44:55.652 --> 44:57.862
♪ ♪

45:07.914 --> 45:10.583
-Where the fuck were you?
-Hey!

45:10.667 --> 45:12.377
I thought you left me! I...

45:12.460 --> 45:14.129
No, you weren’t here
when I woke up!

45:14.212 --> 45:16.756
I didn’t know where you were!
I-I left you a note!

45:16.840 --> 45:19.676
No, I didn’t see any note.

45:19.759 --> 45:21.386
-What is this?
-No, I didn’t...

45:21.469 --> 45:22.929
-I didn’t see that.
-What is this?

45:23.012 --> 45:24.556
I-I did not see it.

45:24.639 --> 45:27.267
-"Be right back."
-Yes, I didn’t see it.

45:27.350 --> 45:30.311
"Kisses, hug, kisses, hug,
Isabel. Love."

45:30.395 --> 45:32.897
-[chuckling] I’m sorry.
-[scoffs]

45:32.981 --> 45:35.400
I went to...

45:35.483 --> 45:38.111
I went to get fertilizer
for Ophelia.

45:38.194 --> 45:39.654
Okay. I...

45:39.737 --> 45:41.614
Yeah, when I woke up,
I was yelling, "Isabel..."

45:41.698 --> 45:43.074
Where are the yellows?

45:43.158 --> 45:45.243
-Uh, they...
-[gasping]

45:45.326 --> 45:48.455
Somebody’s been
in our place, Greg.

45:48.538 --> 45:52.167
The-the-the yellows are missing.

45:52.250 --> 45:55.170
And-and they... they took
the-the drawings of our house.

45:55.253 --> 45:56.880
No, no, I took those.

45:56.963 --> 45:58.381
I got ’em. They’re right here.

45:58.465 --> 46:01.259
Look, I got ’em.
They’re right here.

46:01.342 --> 46:02.719
Why?

46:02.802 --> 46:04.220
Why did you...

46:04.304 --> 46:06.139
Why did you take them away?

46:06.222 --> 46:07.432
No, I...

46:07.515 --> 46:09.142
It’s our memory of our house.

46:09.225 --> 46:10.977
-I just wanted to look at them.
-Are you trying to forget?

46:11.060 --> 46:13.438
No, I’m not trying to forget.
I just wanted to look at them.

46:13.521 --> 46:15.440
Did you take them
because you’re leaving?

46:15.523 --> 46:16.357
No!

46:16.441 --> 46:18.026
I didn’t. I-I felt...

46:18.109 --> 46:20.278
I felt self-conscious
having them there,

46:20.361 --> 46:22.572
’cause it’s like a...

46:25.825 --> 46:27.952
[panting]

46:31.080 --> 46:32.832
[sobbing]

46:32.916 --> 46:34.709
Did you see her?

46:34.792 --> 46:36.127
No.

46:36.211 --> 46:37.837
[sobbing]

46:37.921 --> 46:40.381
Tell me the truth.

46:40.465 --> 46:42.383
-I didn’t see her.
-Why you have that in there?

46:42.467 --> 46:44.302
-I-I did not...
-Did you call her?

46:44.385 --> 46:46.804
No. I-I thought about it,
but I didn’t.

46:46.888 --> 46:49.807
I didn’t... I...
I didn’t see her.

46:49.891 --> 46:51.893
I tried, but-but I-I...

46:51.976 --> 46:53.853
Why is it such a terrible thing?

46:53.937 --> 46:56.147
It’s not supposed
to be happening.

46:56.231 --> 46:59.067
-[panting]
-Isabel... [stammers]

46:59.150 --> 47:00.985
-I didn’t see her.
-I don’t understand.

47:01.069 --> 47:02.403
I didn’t see her.

47:02.487 --> 47:05.240
I’m really worried
about you, Greg.

47:05.323 --> 47:08.243
-I’m really worried about you.
-Okay.

47:08.326 --> 47:09.911
-You’re...
-I’m okay.

47:09.994 --> 47:12.372
You’re getting sucked
into the illusion,

47:12.455 --> 47:14.916
and you’re dragging me
in with you.

47:14.999 --> 47:20.505
I know this is not real,
and I can barely breathe,

47:20.588 --> 47:22.131
and... [gasping]

47:22.215 --> 47:26.928
and-and my stomach is turning,
and my skin hurts,

47:27.011 --> 47:29.180
-and I feel like I’m drowning.
-Isabel, it’s okay, just...

47:29.264 --> 47:32.308
And I know this is not real.

47:33.685 --> 47:38.648
You are getting seduced
by the simulation,

47:38.731 --> 47:41.693
and I’m losing you.

47:41.776 --> 47:44.988
I-I think maybe we should
just stop hanging out.

47:50.368 --> 47:52.537
You’re my soul mate.

47:52.620 --> 47:54.664
You can’t just walk away

47:54.747 --> 47:57.458
and think that
you can disconnect from me.

47:57.542 --> 47:59.627
If you could see the difference
between what’s real

47:59.711 --> 48:01.588
and what’s illusion,
you’d know that.

48:01.671 --> 48:04.090
And you’re supposed
to know that by now.

48:04.173 --> 48:05.883
How am I supposed to know?

48:05.967 --> 48:09.095
Y-You’re the one telling me
he’s real and she’s not real,

48:09.178 --> 48:11.681
and then I have to take
your word for it, right?

48:11.764 --> 48:14.559
That’s really your trick,
is it forces me

48:14.642 --> 48:15.852
-to depend on you.
-No.

48:15.935 --> 48:17.312
No, no, no. It makes me...

48:17.395 --> 48:19.856
It’s very clever.
It makes me believe in you.

48:19.939 --> 48:21.858
But guess what,
I don’t believe in you.

48:21.941 --> 48:23.276
I’ve never believed in you.

48:23.359 --> 48:25.862
How could someone believe you?

48:25.945 --> 48:28.489
Tell me something
that makes me believe in you.

48:28.573 --> 48:31.159
-Show me something.
-Okay.

48:32.785 --> 48:34.704
Okay, I get it.

48:36.998 --> 48:39.626
You... you have to see it
for yourself.

48:39.709 --> 48:41.169
See what?

48:41.252 --> 48:44.005
[Isabel] We have to take
a special kind of crystal,

48:44.088 --> 48:45.465
different from the yellows.

48:47.675 --> 48:51.429
They are very rare.
I got them from Kendo.

48:51.512 --> 48:53.014
They’re blue crystals.

48:53.097 --> 48:55.516
It’s an exit mechanism.

48:55.600 --> 48:58.061
They will eject us
from this simulation.

48:58.144 --> 49:00.980
We have to take ten each.

49:01.064 --> 49:03.983
Two, three, four, five,

49:04.067 --> 49:07.779
six, seven, eight, nine, ten.

49:07.862 --> 49:10.907
One, two, three,
four, five, six.

49:10.990 --> 49:12.575
Shit.

49:12.659 --> 49:14.994
Is-is that enough?

49:15.078 --> 49:17.163
Fuck it. We’ll take the chance.

49:17.246 --> 49:19.207
Where-where did you get
the measurement from?

49:19.290 --> 49:21.250
[Isabel]
It’s theoretical.

49:21.334 --> 49:23.294
I think we’ll be fine.

49:25.505 --> 49:28.591
It has to be taken
through the nose.

49:30.093 --> 49:31.386
Come.

49:38.935 --> 49:40.061
Come on, baby.

49:40.144 --> 49:43.773
We have to exit
this stupid simulation.

49:45.274 --> 49:47.443
Is it safe?

49:48.653 --> 49:50.738
Kind of.

49:52.198 --> 49:54.367
[train passing]

49:55.910 --> 49:57.078
[click, sharp whoosh]

49:57.161 --> 49:59.372
[water bubbling gently]

50:08.881 --> 50:11.050
♪ ♪

50:15.304 --> 50:17.473
[birds chirping]

50:23.354 --> 50:25.606
[water continues
bubbling gently]

50:49.297 --> 50:52.592
Dr. Clemens, you okay?

50:52.675 --> 50:54.802
Yes, we’re okay, Liang.

50:54.886 --> 50:56.053
Don’t panic.

50:56.137 --> 50:58.306
We ejected the brainbox
on purpose.

50:58.389 --> 51:02.059
Dr. Wittle formed an unhealthy
attachment to an FGP again,

51:02.143 --> 51:03.561
and he was dragging me with him.

51:03.644 --> 51:06.105
Oh. And your exit mechanism?

51:06.189 --> 51:08.107
[Isabel]
Blue algorithm, as expected.

51:08.191 --> 51:11.778
But this time, it was
no easy task to get crystals.

51:11.861 --> 51:13.404
Thank God that Kendo
has developed

51:13.488 --> 51:15.031
such a talent for finding them.

51:15.114 --> 51:18.201
Well, if you don’t
mind me asking,

51:18.284 --> 51:20.745
what did this one feel like?

51:20.828 --> 51:25.625
It wasn’t war
or extreme poverty,

51:25.708 --> 51:27.376
but, hell, it was icky.

51:27.460 --> 51:29.796
I’m so glad to...
[inhales deeply]

51:29.879 --> 51:31.923
be able to breathe
this fresh air.

51:32.006 --> 51:35.259
-Please disconnect Dr. Wittle.
-Okay.

51:39.180 --> 51:41.808
Hello, Dr. Wittle.

51:41.891 --> 51:44.185
You feeling okay?

51:44.268 --> 51:46.479
I feel okay.

51:48.147 --> 51:50.399
[exhales, sniffs]

51:50.483 --> 51:52.401
[Liang chuckles]

51:52.485 --> 51:56.113
Well... this...

51:56.197 --> 51:58.574
should get your electrolytes up.

51:58.658 --> 51:59.951
Thank you.

52:00.034 --> 52:01.369
What is it?

52:01.452 --> 52:03.538
Lime Gatorade.

52:04.413 --> 52:05.873
Yeah.

52:05.957 --> 52:08.251
Easy does it. There we go.

52:15.383 --> 52:17.134
There’s my guy.

52:17.218 --> 52:19.929
Welcome home.

52:20.012 --> 52:21.973
What’s a FGP?

52:23.474 --> 52:24.934
[Isabel]
Note the memory gap.

52:25.017 --> 52:26.978
You said "FGP." You were...

52:27.061 --> 52:31.190
Yes, it’s short for
"fake generated person."

52:31.274 --> 52:33.359
Only these volunteers are real.

52:35.319 --> 52:37.029
Did you save our incarnations?

52:37.113 --> 52:39.156
Mm, they’re automatically
in the cloud.

52:39.240 --> 52:40.992
Uh, shall I get it going now?

52:41.075 --> 52:42.410
Give us a couple of hours.

52:42.493 --> 52:45.329
I’m taking Dr. Wittle to lunch.

52:45.413 --> 52:47.790
Sounds good. I’ll be here.

52:52.837 --> 52:55.590
[trilling]

52:55.673 --> 53:00.136
Some FGPs are
more convincing than others.

53:08.936 --> 53:11.105
♪ ♪

53:36.297 --> 53:38.382
[lively chatter]

53:38.466 --> 53:40.009
[birds chirping]

53:44.639 --> 53:46.515
[Greg sighs]

53:50.478 --> 53:52.688
What do you think?

53:56.400 --> 53:59.946
I think this place
is overwhelming.

54:00.029 --> 54:03.658
[Isabel] Good overwhelming
or bad overwhelming?

54:03.741 --> 54:05.660
[Greg]
Great overwhelming.

54:05.743 --> 54:08.245
-[chuckles]
-What’s with all the...

54:09.997 --> 54:13.918
What is with the-the hologram
or the-the ghost people?

54:14.001 --> 54:17.129
Oh. Telepresence.
It’s all the rage these days.

54:18.047 --> 54:19.632
Hello, Dr. Clemens.

54:19.715 --> 54:21.092
Dr. Wittle.

54:21.175 --> 54:22.760
How’s the research coming?

54:22.843 --> 54:24.679
It’s getting there.

54:26.013 --> 54:28.391
Any problems
we should be aware of?

54:29.558 --> 54:30.726
No.

54:30.810 --> 54:33.020
-Mm. Mm.
-Lovely to see you.

54:37.525 --> 54:39.902
-That was quite a look
she was giving you. -[sighs]

54:39.986 --> 54:43.197
-Any problems I should
be aware of? -[laughs]

54:43.280 --> 54:44.532
Are you okay?

54:44.615 --> 54:47.201
Yeah, yeah, I’m good, I’m good.

54:47.284 --> 54:49.537
Would you like to take
the scenic route?

54:49.620 --> 54:50.955
Yes.

54:51.038 --> 54:53.207
♪ ♪

55:01.048 --> 55:03.759
[Greg] Now, why am I not
remembering any of this?

55:03.843 --> 55:05.594
Don’t worry about it.

55:05.678 --> 55:08.014
Sometimes it happens
to the volunteers.

55:08.097 --> 55:10.057
To some of them, anyway.

55:10.141 --> 55:11.559
It’ll wear off.

55:11.642 --> 55:13.853
♪ ♪

55:16.605 --> 55:19.525
-[man] Think fast, Greggo.
-Hi. Oh.

55:22.069 --> 55:24.447
Good on you, bud. Mm!

55:25.322 --> 55:28.701
Oh, put that brain boner away.

55:28.784 --> 55:30.369
We got to get some olive oil.

55:30.453 --> 55:32.079
-Oh, no, Greg.
-Yes.

55:32.163 --> 55:34.874
-No, we have gallons
of it at home. -Yes.

55:34.957 --> 55:37.251
Home?

55:44.800 --> 55:46.969
♪ ♪

56:04.904 --> 56:07.656
[Isabel chuckles]

56:07.740 --> 56:09.992
I can’t believe it.

56:10.076 --> 56:12.787
[Isabel]
I told you.

56:17.500 --> 56:19.752
Hotel Pleiades.

56:19.835 --> 56:21.170
Yeah.

56:21.253 --> 56:24.090
What a fantastic name
for a hotel

56:24.173 --> 56:26.842
that has its own observatory.

56:26.926 --> 56:29.303
"Play at ease."

56:35.976 --> 56:38.187
♪ ♪

56:49.115 --> 56:51.617
♪ ♪

57:10.344 --> 57:12.555
♪ ♪

57:27.862 --> 57:29.864
[sighs]

57:29.947 --> 57:32.158
[birds chirping]

57:51.302 --> 57:54.638
How did this whole world
come to be?

57:59.435 --> 58:01.187
Your memory’s not back.

58:01.270 --> 58:02.980
No.

58:03.063 --> 58:04.607
Is that bad?

58:07.026 --> 58:10.404
I was so scared to lose you.

58:10.487 --> 58:15.409
I made an irresponsible
and stupid decision.

58:15.492 --> 58:17.953
We shouldn’t have exited
like that,

58:18.037 --> 58:21.290
without the appropriate
dosage and...

58:21.373 --> 58:23.876
[sighs] Maybe it might...
it might not come back.

58:23.959 --> 58:25.169
Who cares?

58:25.252 --> 58:27.129
I love not remembering
this place,

58:27.213 --> 58:30.799
because I get to
discover it all again.

58:30.883 --> 58:33.469
I’m walking around
just like a newborn,

58:33.552 --> 58:38.766
experiencing all of this beauty
for the first time.

58:38.849 --> 58:41.352
I just want to know, is it...
where did it come from?

58:41.435 --> 58:43.270
Has it always been like this?

58:46.190 --> 58:48.776
No. [chuckles]

58:48.859 --> 58:51.528
This place was actually
much worse

58:51.612 --> 58:53.656
than the one we just exited.

58:55.449 --> 58:58.160
It got so bad.

58:58.244 --> 59:01.080
I mean,
pollution was to a degree

59:01.163 --> 59:03.916
that people would just
drop dead on the street,

59:03.999 --> 59:08.420
and the level of poverty
was insufferable. It...

59:08.504 --> 59:09.797
I can’t...

59:09.880 --> 59:12.091
Looking at this,
I can’t picture that.

59:12.174 --> 59:13.592
I mean, what happened?

59:13.676 --> 59:15.177
Three things.

59:15.261 --> 59:16.553
Just three things?

59:16.637 --> 59:17.846
-Mm. Yeah.
-Okay.

59:17.930 --> 59:19.139
-Can you guess?
-No.

59:19.223 --> 59:21.100
-Oh, come on.
-I don’t know.

59:21.183 --> 59:23.143
Automation,

59:23.227 --> 59:25.396
synthetic biology

59:25.479 --> 59:28.440
and asteroid mining.

59:28.524 --> 59:31.402
I wasn’t gonna guess that.

59:31.485 --> 59:32.861
[gasps]

59:32.945 --> 59:34.905
Oh, I have... Oh, wait.

59:34.989 --> 59:36.782
I’m gonna get your memory back.

59:36.865 --> 59:38.409
I’m gonna get your mem...

59:38.492 --> 59:40.661
I’m gonna trigger that memory.

59:40.744 --> 59:43.747
-You’re coming back. Watch this.
-[laughing]

59:45.040 --> 59:46.333
I’m scared.

59:46.417 --> 59:48.627
Yes!

59:50.421 --> 59:51.672
Ta-da!

59:51.755 --> 59:54.216
The Thought Visualizer.

59:54.300 --> 59:56.593
[beeping]

59:59.555 --> 1:00:02.057
You don’t remember your baby?

1:00:03.767 --> 1:00:05.686
This is your invention.

1:00:05.769 --> 1:00:07.229
I invented that?

1:00:07.313 --> 1:00:10.149
Oh, it’s, like, super popular

1:00:10.232 --> 1:00:13.027
in very small circles.
[chuckles]

1:00:13.110 --> 1:00:14.903
Give it a try.

1:00:14.987 --> 1:00:16.822
What is it?

1:00:16.905 --> 1:00:20.242
A Thought... Visualizer.

1:00:20.326 --> 1:00:22.328
Okay, but I don’t know
what that is.

1:00:22.411 --> 1:00:24.204
Okay, introduce yourself.

1:00:24.288 --> 1:00:25.456
Hello.

1:00:25.539 --> 1:00:29.126
I’m Greg Wittle.

1:00:29.209 --> 1:00:31.587
[melodic beeping]

1:00:31.670 --> 1:00:33.714
[Isabel chuckles]

1:00:34.840 --> 1:00:36.050
Strawberries.

1:00:36.133 --> 1:00:38.635
A dinosaur...

1:00:38.719 --> 1:00:40.471
swimming in the ocean.

1:00:40.554 --> 1:00:43.932
A cheetah chasing a gazelle.

1:00:44.016 --> 1:00:45.893
-A volcano.
-[chuckles]

1:00:45.976 --> 1:00:47.394
[Isabel]
Oh, my favorite one.

1:00:47.478 --> 1:00:49.521
Do my favorite one. Say...

1:00:49.605 --> 1:00:51.857
[whispers]
"We’re in a pickle."

1:00:51.940 --> 1:00:54.234
[Isabel chuckling]

1:00:55.527 --> 1:00:57.321
We’re in a pickle.

1:00:57.404 --> 1:00:59.448
-[both laughing]
-[beeping "Shave and a Haircut"]

1:00:59.531 --> 1:01:01.241
I love it.

1:01:01.325 --> 1:01:03.702
But you know what?
This is not just a toy.

1:01:03.786 --> 1:01:06.997
It’s amazing
for illustrating things.

1:01:07.081 --> 1:01:10.876
Sit up straight
and pay attention, Dr. Wittle.

1:01:10.959 --> 1:01:13.921
Science saved the world.

1:01:14.004 --> 1:01:18.884
Synthetic biology fixed
all the environmental problems.

1:01:18.967 --> 1:01:21.970
And asteroid mining

1:01:22.054 --> 1:01:25.641
brought mountains of new money.

1:01:25.724 --> 1:01:29.853
And the guy that had the company
for the asteroid mining...

1:01:29.937 --> 1:01:31.814
-That guy.
-Yeah.

1:01:31.897 --> 1:01:35.567
He just started giving
all this free money away.

1:01:35.651 --> 1:01:38.320
I mean, every single person here

1:01:38.404 --> 1:01:41.698
gets a base of 500,000K a year.

1:01:41.782 --> 1:01:45.035
And, of course, then the robots,
they started doing

1:01:45.119 --> 1:01:48.038
all the boring
and tedious tasks.

1:01:48.122 --> 1:01:52.751
We had the freedom and the time
to explore our passions:

1:01:52.835 --> 1:01:57.256
science, art, whatever,
whatever you wanted.

1:01:57.339 --> 1:01:59.800
We went from a broken world

1:01:59.883 --> 1:02:03.011
to a beautiful, sustainable,

1:02:03.095 --> 1:02:05.139
safe, peaceful Earth.

1:02:05.222 --> 1:02:08.100
You have to admit,

1:02:08.183 --> 1:02:09.726
this is spectacular.

1:02:11.395 --> 1:02:12.813
Yes.

1:02:14.022 --> 1:02:16.650
-But you know what?
-What?

1:02:19.111 --> 1:02:21.280
The thing is that...

1:02:21.363 --> 1:02:24.241
it’s amazing how easy

1:02:24.324 --> 1:02:28.036
humans can get used to
even something spectacular.

1:02:28.120 --> 1:02:31.874
Most people say,
"Ignorance is bliss,"

1:02:31.957 --> 1:02:34.376
but I say...

1:02:34.460 --> 1:02:39.047
you have to experience the good
to appreciate the bad.

1:02:39.131 --> 1:02:41.425
No, the other way around.

1:02:42.885 --> 1:02:44.720
Exactly.

1:02:44.803 --> 1:02:48.432
So that’s where
the brainbox comes from.

1:02:53.228 --> 1:02:54.521
It works.

1:02:54.605 --> 1:02:55.939
You really mean that?

1:02:56.023 --> 1:02:58.108
-Yes.
-You really think it works?

1:02:58.192 --> 1:03:01.069
Look at me. [scoffs]

1:03:01.153 --> 1:03:04.573
I’m sitting here.
I couldn’t be more...

1:03:10.746 --> 1:03:13.123
I couldn’t be more grateful.

1:03:13.207 --> 1:03:15.083
Greg.

1:03:15.167 --> 1:03:17.169
Let’s go for a swim.

1:03:17.252 --> 1:03:19.755
-Oh, we can’t.
-Yes, we can.

1:03:19.838 --> 1:03:22.299
-No, we have to go back.
-No.

1:03:22.382 --> 1:03:24.384
No, we have to go
back to the lab.

1:03:24.468 --> 1:03:27.012
We will, in a little bit.

1:03:27.095 --> 1:03:28.931
Come on.

1:03:29.014 --> 1:03:31.225
No, I have to take this
very seriously.

1:03:31.308 --> 1:03:32.935
I know.
I’m taking it seriously, too.

1:03:33.018 --> 1:03:35.103
But you can’t just give me
a bite of an apple

1:03:35.187 --> 1:03:37.856
-and then show it and then take
it away. -I already messed up.

1:03:37.940 --> 1:03:39.691
Give me another...
give me another couple bites.

1:03:39.775 --> 1:03:41.777
-I already exited before it was
over because of you. -I know.

1:03:41.860 --> 1:03:44.071
Listen, listen, listen,
listen, listen, listen, listen.

1:03:44.154 --> 1:03:45.739
We are gonna go back.

1:03:45.822 --> 1:03:48.408
We’re just gonna
just crunch into this apple

1:03:48.492 --> 1:03:51.537
-for a few more days, and then
we’re going back. -[sighs]

1:03:51.620 --> 1:03:54.748
But first, we’re gonna swim.
Come on.

1:03:55.958 --> 1:03:57.918
I’m scared.

1:03:58.001 --> 1:03:59.336
[Isabel sighs]

1:03:59.419 --> 1:04:00.712
-Shut up.
-[chuckling]

1:04:00.796 --> 1:04:02.881
Just shut the fuck up.

1:04:05.717 --> 1:04:07.594
Just one day.

1:04:07.678 --> 1:04:09.513
One more day.

1:04:09.596 --> 1:04:11.473
That’s it.

1:04:12.599 --> 1:04:14.768
♪ ♪

1:04:39.418 --> 1:04:42.087
Whoo!

1:04:42.170 --> 1:04:43.797
-[Greg] Careful.
-[lively chatter]

1:04:43.880 --> 1:04:46.466
Is there a little bit
of a shindig going on?

1:04:46.550 --> 1:04:49.052
-A what?
-Soiree.

1:04:49.136 --> 1:04:50.429
A fiesta.

1:04:50.512 --> 1:04:52.431
Oh, yes!

1:04:52.514 --> 1:04:53.974
The mixer!

1:04:54.057 --> 1:04:56.143
Artists and scientists
get together twice a month,

1:04:56.226 --> 1:04:57.686
and I forgot it was today.

1:04:57.769 --> 1:05:00.939
Oh, who’s having
the memory problem now, honey?

1:05:01.023 --> 1:05:03.525
Now, don’t worry, it happens
to some of the volunteers.

1:05:03.609 --> 1:05:06.236
-It should come back, hopefully.
-Cállate.

1:05:06.320 --> 1:05:08.447
[lively chatter]

1:05:08.530 --> 1:05:11.867
So, is this how you imagined it?

1:05:12.868 --> 1:05:15.245
Hmm? The Hotel Pleiades?

1:05:17.205 --> 1:05:18.582
Mm!

1:05:20.626 --> 1:05:22.711
[chuckles] Thanks.

1:05:26.089 --> 1:05:28.091
It’s so nice, huh?

1:05:29.259 --> 1:05:30.510
Hi.

1:05:30.594 --> 1:05:32.304
-Dr. Clemens.
-[Isabel gasps]

1:05:32.387 --> 1:05:34.556
-Oh, Dr. Nye.
-It’s so good to see you.

1:05:34.640 --> 1:05:36.391
-Thanks for taking the time.
-Yes.

1:05:36.475 --> 1:05:37.643
Hope you’re having a good time.

1:05:37.726 --> 1:05:38.852
We’re having a great time.
You remember Greg?

1:05:38.935 --> 1:05:39.978
Dr. Wittle?

1:05:40.062 --> 1:05:41.855
-Yes, Greg.
-Yes, we ordered one of

1:05:41.938 --> 1:05:43.774
your Thought Visualizers.

1:05:43.857 --> 1:05:45.859
[chuckles]
It’s a lot of fun.

1:05:45.942 --> 1:05:48.945
-Have you ever said to it,
"I’m in a pickle"? -Yeah.

1:05:49.029 --> 1:05:50.238
-Have you ever done that?
-We...

1:05:50.322 --> 1:05:51.365
[laughs]
It’s so good.

1:05:51.448 --> 1:05:52.866
No, listen, "I’m in a pickle."

1:05:52.949 --> 1:05:54.284
-Next time, you try it.
-Okay.

1:05:54.368 --> 1:05:55.744
It’s amazing.

1:05:55.827 --> 1:05:57.329
-Well, you two look so good.
-[Isabel] Thank you.

1:05:57.412 --> 1:05:58.914
-So do you. -Uh, thank you
for taking the time.

1:05:58.997 --> 1:06:00.874
-[chuckles] Oh, this?
-[Isabel] Yes.

1:06:00.957 --> 1:06:03.001
I throw it on
when I don’t care how I look.

1:06:03.085 --> 1:06:04.920
-[Isabel laughs]
-Now, carry on, you crazy kids.

1:06:05.003 --> 1:06:06.213
-Okay.
-Thank you.

1:06:06.296 --> 1:06:07.464
-Enjoy.
-Thanks.

1:06:07.547 --> 1:06:11.468
He got your Thought Visualizer.

1:06:11.551 --> 1:06:13.970
Wow. Oh, wow.

1:06:14.054 --> 1:06:15.931
Now I’m impressed.

1:06:16.014 --> 1:06:18.850
[Slavoj Zizek]
Maybe, just maybe, hell...

1:06:18.934 --> 1:06:21.520
is not such a horrible place.

1:06:21.603 --> 1:06:23.063
Whenever I hear about,

1:06:23.146 --> 1:06:25.857
"Oh, my God,
boiling oil in hell,"

1:06:25.941 --> 1:06:30.320
my first expectation is
wild partying, barbecue,

1:06:30.404 --> 1:06:34.282
-sexual orgies, alcohol,
and so on and so on. -[laughs]

1:06:34.366 --> 1:06:37.327
What if this is
the real life in hell?

1:06:37.411 --> 1:06:39.788
And what if, in hell,

1:06:39.871 --> 1:06:43.959
from time to time,
some devil’s representative

1:06:44.042 --> 1:06:47.629
comes to the people having a
good time there and tells them,

1:06:47.713 --> 1:06:50.799
"Listen, guys, now we will be
for a quarter of an hour

1:06:50.882 --> 1:06:56.179
observed by heaven, so please
pretend that you suffer."

1:06:56.263 --> 1:06:58.265
[laughter, lively chatter]

1:07:04.062 --> 1:07:07.107
-Hey, I’m glad
I caught you alone. -Yeah.

1:07:07.190 --> 1:07:08.900
There’s something
I want to tell you.

1:07:08.984 --> 1:07:10.777
Word on the street is
there’ve been problems

1:07:10.861 --> 1:07:12.404
with Isabel’s research.

1:07:12.487 --> 1:07:15.490
You heard anything?
You know anything about that?

1:07:15.574 --> 1:07:16.616
No, I...

1:07:16.700 --> 1:07:18.118
I’ve gotten a good feeling.

1:07:18.201 --> 1:07:20.579
Okay.
We all want her to succeed,

1:07:20.662 --> 1:07:23.915
but this is her reputation
on the line.

1:07:23.999 --> 1:07:26.209
♪ ♪

1:07:29.546 --> 1:07:31.548
-What did he say?
-[chuckling]

1:07:31.631 --> 1:07:33.800
What did he want?

1:07:39.473 --> 1:07:41.391
What did he say to you?

1:07:41.475 --> 1:07:45.228
He said that everybody
really wants you to succeed.

1:07:45.312 --> 1:07:46.855
[scoffs]

1:07:50.317 --> 1:07:52.110
-Really? -I don’t think
that’s a bad thing

1:07:52.194 --> 1:07:53.820
that everybody wants you
to succeed.

1:07:53.904 --> 1:07:56.198
Ah, then why didn’t you
tell me what he was saying?

1:07:56.281 --> 1:07:57.991
This is bullshit.
You think I believe that?

1:07:58.074 --> 1:08:00.535
-You think I’m stupid?
-Isabel, he came up to me...

1:08:00.619 --> 1:08:03.580
You think I don’t know that
these people are laughing at me?

1:08:03.663 --> 1:08:05.582
What the fuck
are you looking at?

1:08:05.665 --> 1:08:07.250
Isabel. Isabel.
Hey, hey, hey, hey, hey.

1:08:07.334 --> 1:08:09.503
No, no, no, no, no, no, no, no.
Nobody here believes in me.

1:08:09.586 --> 1:08:11.463
-They want you to succeed.
-Yeah, right.

1:08:11.546 --> 1:08:13.089
Don’t say "nobody here."
I’m here.

1:08:13.173 --> 1:08:14.549
-You’re taking their side!
-Listen.

1:08:14.633 --> 1:08:17.093
I’m here, and I believe in you.

1:08:17.177 --> 1:08:18.845
Right?

1:08:22.516 --> 1:08:25.519
I believe in everything
that you’re doing.

1:08:28.355 --> 1:08:31.900
Your patience with me
is a thing of beauty.

1:08:31.983 --> 1:08:34.820
Let’s get out of here.

1:08:34.903 --> 1:08:37.072
[party guest]
My grandmother used to say,

1:08:37.155 --> 1:08:40.450
"The universe is sitting
on the back of a tortoise."

1:08:40.534 --> 1:08:42.369
And I would ask Granny,

1:08:42.452 --> 1:08:44.621
"What is that tortoise
standing on?"

1:08:44.704 --> 1:08:47.916
She replied
with quite confidence,

1:08:47.999 --> 1:08:50.126
"Another tortoise.

1:08:50.210 --> 1:08:52.921
"And that one stands
on another tortoise.

1:08:53.004 --> 1:08:55.924
And that one, another tortoise."

1:08:56.007 --> 1:09:01.471
It turns out
it’s turtles all the way down.

1:09:01.555 --> 1:09:02.681
[siren wailing in distance]

1:09:02.764 --> 1:09:04.724
I wouldn’t go near him, ma’am.

1:09:04.808 --> 1:09:07.060
He could be unpredictable.

1:09:09.479 --> 1:09:11.314
[train horn blows]

1:09:13.525 --> 1:09:15.735
[birds chirping]

1:09:43.263 --> 1:09:45.098
Whew.

1:09:46.141 --> 1:09:48.101
It’s a little cold.

1:09:48.184 --> 1:09:49.769
Was not expecting that.

1:09:49.853 --> 1:09:52.355
Complaining already.

1:09:52.439 --> 1:09:55.150
I’m fine. It’s just chilly.

1:09:56.192 --> 1:09:57.819
I get one shot at this.

1:09:57.903 --> 1:09:59.821
One shot.

1:09:59.905 --> 1:10:02.240
I’m gonna show these arrogant,

1:10:02.324 --> 1:10:05.285
patronizing son of a bitches

1:10:05.368 --> 1:10:10.290
that access to the brainbox--
it’s a human right.

1:10:17.255 --> 1:10:19.382
Publish now. Stop being afraid.

1:10:19.466 --> 1:10:21.509
Just get it out there
and let people decide then.

1:10:21.593 --> 1:10:24.846
We have to go back
into the brainbox, Greg.

1:10:24.930 --> 1:10:27.223
I need complete data.

1:10:27.307 --> 1:10:29.684
We need to finish the cycle.

1:10:29.768 --> 1:10:32.604
You have enough data, Isabel.

1:10:32.687 --> 1:10:35.357
Not to mention the fact
that I’m not going back in.

1:10:35.440 --> 1:10:36.983
[sighs]

1:10:37.067 --> 1:10:41.821
Just stop doubting yourself.

1:10:41.905 --> 1:10:45.408
Why do you care so much
what they think?

1:10:45.492 --> 1:10:47.702
Put it out there.

1:10:47.786 --> 1:10:49.537
They’re gonna think it’s great.

1:10:51.665 --> 1:10:53.875
And if they don’t...

1:10:54.793 --> 1:10:57.504
And if they don’t?

1:10:57.587 --> 1:11:02.050
Then here we are,
right here, together.

1:11:03.635 --> 1:11:05.720
[shudders]

1:11:05.804 --> 1:11:08.682
Weren’t you telling me
that we were soul mates?

1:11:12.060 --> 1:11:14.938
Would you let me
interview you onstage?

1:11:18.108 --> 1:11:20.777
It would be my honor.

1:11:20.860 --> 1:11:24.030
[Dr. Huang] Our presenter,
Dr. Isabel Clemens,

1:11:24.114 --> 1:11:27.158
pioneered brainbox simulations,

1:11:27.242 --> 1:11:30.745
ugly, simulated worlds
that users can jack into

1:11:30.829 --> 1:11:34.541
in order to generate
appreciation for the real world.

1:11:34.624 --> 1:11:35.959
-Dr. Clemens.
-[applause]

1:11:36.042 --> 1:11:37.252
[Isabel]
Thank you very much.

1:11:37.335 --> 1:11:39.170
[applause continues]

1:11:39.254 --> 1:11:41.381
What is bliss?

1:11:41.464 --> 1:11:43.425
Bliss is not a feeling.

1:11:43.508 --> 1:11:45.010
It’s not a place.

1:11:45.093 --> 1:11:48.805
Bliss is a state of mind
that can only be achieved

1:11:48.888 --> 1:11:51.558
by understanding the contrast

1:11:51.641 --> 1:11:54.894
with the opposite state of mind.

1:11:54.978 --> 1:12:00.066
But the proof is in the pudding.

1:12:00.150 --> 1:12:02.610
Please meet my pudding,

1:12:02.694 --> 1:12:04.821
Dr. Wittle.

1:12:04.904 --> 1:12:06.948
[applause]

1:12:07.032 --> 1:12:09.951
Please take a seat, Dr. Wittle.

1:12:10.035 --> 1:12:14.039
Before we have a volunteer
connected to the brainbox,

1:12:14.122 --> 1:12:16.958
we always ask
a series of questions.

1:12:17.042 --> 1:12:20.378
And now I will ask Dr. Wittle
the same questions

1:12:20.462 --> 1:12:25.091
so we can compare his responses
to the previous ones.

1:12:25.175 --> 1:12:29.012
Dr. Wittle,
how do you feel right now?

1:12:29.095 --> 1:12:31.389
♪ ♪

1:12:37.645 --> 1:12:39.939
I feel great.
I’m happy to be here.

1:12:40.023 --> 1:12:44.944
And thank you
for the nice reception.

1:12:45.028 --> 1:12:46.946
-[Isabel on video]
Dr. Wittle... -Yes.

1:12:47.030 --> 1:12:48.698
...how do you feel right now?

1:12:48.782 --> 1:12:51.117
Fine. Great.

1:12:51.201 --> 1:12:52.660
Yeah, sure.

1:12:52.744 --> 1:12:54.788
I mean, is that really
the first question,

1:12:54.871 --> 1:12:58.208
or are we just bullshitting
till you start?

1:13:01.753 --> 1:13:04.214
Any complaints, Dr. Wittle?

1:13:04.297 --> 1:13:06.508
No. None at all.

1:13:06.591 --> 1:13:11.179
I feel like I’ve died
and gone to heaven.

1:13:11.262 --> 1:13:13.640
Without the dying part.

1:13:13.723 --> 1:13:15.391
[Isabel on video]
Dr. Wittle...

1:13:15.475 --> 1:13:17.685
-Yes.
-...do you have any complaints?

1:13:17.769 --> 1:13:20.355
Other than being your lab rat?

1:13:20.438 --> 1:13:23.274
Just the usual
ups and downs of life.

1:13:23.358 --> 1:13:24.609
Um...

1:13:24.692 --> 1:13:26.820
I mean, can I... should I
be petty for a second?

1:13:26.903 --> 1:13:28.238
I’m a little frustrated.

1:13:28.321 --> 1:13:29.948
I can’t get
the pool temperature,

1:13:30.031 --> 1:13:31.574
you know, to work.

1:13:31.658 --> 1:13:34.452
I mean, how fucking difficult
is it to get a pool heated

1:13:34.536 --> 1:13:36.955
to, uh, something where you
don’t feel like you’re joining

1:13:37.038 --> 1:13:39.499
the Polar Bear Club
when you jump in?

1:13:42.127 --> 1:13:43.545
[Isabel]
Dr. Wittle,

1:13:43.628 --> 1:13:45.880
do you feel like
you are lacking anything

1:13:45.964 --> 1:13:48.466
or anyone
in your life right now?

1:13:50.760 --> 1:13:52.929
♪ ♪

1:14:16.661 --> 1:14:19.122
[audience murmuring quietly]

1:14:19.205 --> 1:14:21.207
[Isabel]
Dr. Wittle?

1:14:22.375 --> 1:14:23.585
Greg.

1:14:28.047 --> 1:14:31.301
I don’t feel like
I’m lacking anything.

1:14:33.845 --> 1:14:36.264
-[Isabel on video] Dr. Wittle.
-Yes, Dr. Clemens.

1:14:36.347 --> 1:14:38.683
Do you feel like
you are lacking anything

1:14:38.766 --> 1:14:41.686
or anyone
in your life right now?

1:14:41.769 --> 1:14:43.438
[stammers]

1:14:43.521 --> 1:14:47.025
That’s a...
that’s a dumb question.

1:14:47.108 --> 1:14:49.319
I’m kidding. I’m just joking.

1:14:49.402 --> 1:14:51.571
[Isabel]
Please answer and be honest.

1:14:51.654 --> 1:14:54.908
-That’s how this works.
-[Greg on video] Okay.

1:14:54.991 --> 1:14:56.284
That’s how this works.

1:14:56.367 --> 1:14:59.078
Um... yes.

1:15:00.455 --> 1:15:02.415
Yeah, there is
something missing,

1:15:02.498 --> 1:15:04.751
but I don’t want
to talk about it.

1:15:07.879 --> 1:15:10.173
Well, as you can see,

1:15:10.256 --> 1:15:15.011
this once frustrated
and grumpy man...

1:15:16.512 --> 1:15:20.642
...is now a man
full of wonder and...

1:15:20.725 --> 1:15:22.602
[chuckles]

1:15:22.685 --> 1:15:25.313
...and appreciation

1:15:25.396 --> 1:15:30.610
and a hunger for tasting
every breath of life.

1:15:30.693 --> 1:15:32.904
[applause]

1:15:36.074 --> 1:15:38.409
[cheering]

1:15:38.493 --> 1:15:40.036
Thank you. Thank you.

1:15:40.119 --> 1:15:41.621
-[lively chatter]
-[gentle piano music playing]

1:15:41.704 --> 1:15:44.082
Congratulations, Isabel.
You proved everybody wrong.

1:15:44.165 --> 1:15:45.583
Thank you so much.

1:15:45.667 --> 1:15:47.293
Listen, I read your thesis,

1:15:47.377 --> 1:15:50.171
and I’m gonna submit it
to nature and science magazines

1:15:50.255 --> 1:15:52.257
and hope they put it
on the cover.

1:15:52.340 --> 1:15:53.841
-It’s fantastic.
-Oh...

1:15:53.925 --> 1:15:56.219
-I don’t know what to say.
-Hang on.

1:15:56.302 --> 1:15:58.638
There may be a chaired position
in your future.

1:15:59.889 --> 1:16:01.849
Oh, I have to tell Greg.

1:16:01.933 --> 1:16:04.143
Has anybody seen Dr. Wittle?

1:16:04.227 --> 1:16:05.520
-Thank you.
-Sure.

1:16:05.603 --> 1:16:07.105
-Hey.
-And for you, sir?

1:16:07.188 --> 1:16:09.440
-Cabernet Sauvignon.
-[clears throat]

1:16:13.987 --> 1:16:15.947
Champagne.

1:16:23.121 --> 1:16:25.915
♪ ♪

1:16:31.045 --> 1:16:32.964
Wait. What...

1:16:33.047 --> 1:16:34.215
Excuse me.

1:16:34.299 --> 1:16:35.425
Wait, let me just say hello.

1:16:35.508 --> 1:16:36.759
-[woman] Dr. Clemens.
-Hey.

1:16:36.843 --> 1:16:38.553
Where did the initial idea
come from?

1:16:38.636 --> 1:16:39.804
What was the germ?

1:16:39.887 --> 1:16:41.389
-Yeah...
-Yes, congratulations, Doctor.

1:16:41.472 --> 1:16:43.766
-[chuckles] Thank you. Thank you
very much. -Lovely work.

1:16:43.850 --> 1:16:46.436
Um, I got to go
find someone right now.

1:16:47.687 --> 1:16:49.063
Hey, please, just stop.

1:16:49.147 --> 1:16:51.107
I just want... I just want
to hear your voice.

1:16:51.190 --> 1:16:52.775
Are...

1:16:52.859 --> 1:16:55.987
Are you really here
in this place?

1:16:57.280 --> 1:16:58.489
Yes.

1:16:58.573 --> 1:17:00.116
I’m here with you.

1:17:00.199 --> 1:17:02.285
[Greg]
So you’re real.

1:17:02.368 --> 1:17:03.911
Yes, I’m real.

1:17:03.995 --> 1:17:05.413
You’re in Isabel’s study?

1:17:05.496 --> 1:17:06.998
You’re in Dr. Clemens’ study?

1:17:07.081 --> 1:17:08.249
You’re one of the volunteers?

1:17:08.333 --> 1:17:10.209
-My name is Emily.
-No, I know.

1:17:10.293 --> 1:17:11.210
I’m Emily.

1:17:11.294 --> 1:17:12.545
I know who you are,

1:17:12.628 --> 1:17:14.589
but how are you out here
in the real world?

1:17:14.672 --> 1:17:16.299
I’m your daughter.

1:17:16.382 --> 1:17:18.176
I-I know... [sighs]

1:17:18.259 --> 1:17:21.429
I don’t think I have
a real daughter

1:17:21.512 --> 1:17:23.473
out here in the real world.

1:17:23.556 --> 1:17:27.518
Your name is Greg Wittle.

1:17:28.561 --> 1:17:31.939
You have a son and a daughter.

1:17:32.023 --> 1:17:34.400
Arthur and Emily.

1:17:34.484 --> 1:17:36.069
You’re not thinking clearly

1:17:36.152 --> 1:17:38.654
because your head’s
not on straight.

1:17:41.366 --> 1:17:44.494
I’ve been to your tent, Daddy.

1:17:50.291 --> 1:17:52.293
It’s okay.

1:17:56.005 --> 1:17:59.050
Yeah, it’s just hard
to figure out what’s what.

1:18:00.385 --> 1:18:01.928
’Cause it starts to feel
like there’s, like...

1:18:02.011 --> 1:18:03.554
it’s almost like
a trick being played.

1:18:03.638 --> 1:18:05.765
Um...

1:18:07.433 --> 1:18:10.686
When I was six,

1:18:10.770 --> 1:18:13.856
you, uh... you were
tucking me into bed, and...

1:18:15.441 --> 1:18:17.068
I said, "Careful. Careful.

1:18:17.151 --> 1:18:19.070
I don’t want you
to mess up my braids."

1:18:19.153 --> 1:18:23.074
And you said, "My love,
I can’t mess up your brains.

1:18:23.157 --> 1:18:27.203
They’re inside your head,
protected by your skeleton."

1:18:27.286 --> 1:18:31.749
And I said, "No, my braids, Dad.

1:18:31.833 --> 1:18:34.877
[chuckling]
My braids, not my brains."

1:18:34.961 --> 1:18:38.423
Braids. Braids.

1:18:38.506 --> 1:18:40.758
Braids, not brains.

1:18:40.842 --> 1:18:42.969
[chuckling]
You remember.

1:18:43.052 --> 1:18:45.179
Yes, I remember.

1:18:45.263 --> 1:18:46.931
[sighs]

1:18:47.014 --> 1:18:50.268
[crowd clamoring angrily]

1:18:52.687 --> 1:18:53.938
[gasping]

1:18:54.021 --> 1:18:55.565
[woman] Dr. Clemens,
tell us about the germ.

1:18:55.648 --> 1:18:56.899
-What do you know about it?
-[clamoring continues]

1:18:56.983 --> 1:18:59.694
[Greg]
Dr. Clemens posits that

1:18:59.777 --> 1:19:02.864
these memory echoes
from the brainbox world

1:19:02.947 --> 1:19:04.490
will fade away.

1:19:04.574 --> 1:19:08.744
They’re just a side effect from
not having enough blue crystals.

1:19:08.828 --> 1:19:12.373
-[clamoring continues]
-[protestors chanting]

1:19:13.458 --> 1:19:15.293
One of these days,

1:19:15.376 --> 1:19:19.589
you’re going to have to choose
between these worlds,

1:19:19.672 --> 1:19:23.259
and maybe, somehow,

1:19:23.342 --> 1:19:25.261
to you,

1:19:25.344 --> 1:19:28.139
they’re both real.

1:19:30.099 --> 1:19:33.519
So just... just...

1:19:34.687 --> 1:19:36.856
...just do what’s best
for you, okay?

1:19:36.939 --> 1:19:38.274
[clamoring continues]

1:19:38.357 --> 1:19:39.901
-[Isabel] Greg!
-[woman] Dr. Clemens!

1:19:39.984 --> 1:19:42.278
-[whooshing]
-[voices distorting]

1:19:47.492 --> 1:19:49.202
[Greg]
Isabel!

1:19:49.285 --> 1:19:51.120
[woman]
Get off me!

1:19:51.204 --> 1:19:54.207
[train passing, horn blowing]

1:19:54.290 --> 1:19:55.458
Isabel!

1:19:55.541 --> 1:19:56.542
Greg!

1:19:56.626 --> 1:19:58.294
Greg! Greg!

1:20:07.386 --> 1:20:09.222
-[deep whoosh]
-[people gasping]

1:20:10.848 --> 1:20:12.725
[Isabel]
Shit.

1:20:15.603 --> 1:20:17.063
Did you see that?
I used the powers.

1:20:17.146 --> 1:20:18.397
But that’s impossible.

1:20:18.481 --> 1:20:20.274
-This shouldn’t work here.
-[clamoring]

1:20:20.358 --> 1:20:23.027
-[siren wailing]
-[glass shatters]

1:20:30.201 --> 1:20:32.578
Greg, this is really bad.

1:20:37.792 --> 1:20:40.461
[man in distance]
Poverty’s killing us!

1:20:40.545 --> 1:20:42.213
[Isabel]
We have to get to the lab!

1:20:42.296 --> 1:20:43.631
We need more blue crystals.

1:20:43.714 --> 1:20:45.216
[Greg]
But why would we go back in?

1:20:45.299 --> 1:20:46.759
That’s a terrible idea.

1:20:46.842 --> 1:20:48.219
[Isabel]
We took eight instead of ten.

1:20:48.302 --> 1:20:49.762
[Greg] But you said
that was theoretical.

1:20:49.845 --> 1:20:50.930
It was just an estimate.

1:20:51.013 --> 1:20:52.682
[Isabel]
Well, I guess I got that

1:20:52.765 --> 1:20:54.350
little fucking detail wrong,
didn’t I?

1:20:54.433 --> 1:20:56.435
No, you’ve got to explain
anything to me!

1:20:56.519 --> 1:20:57.603
[Isabel]
This is what I know.

1:20:57.687 --> 1:20:59.605
The brainbox cells
must have worked

1:20:59.689 --> 1:21:01.065
their way into our head.

1:21:01.148 --> 1:21:02.692
It’s as if we are bringing

1:21:02.775 --> 1:21:04.944
some of the simulation
here with us

1:21:05.027 --> 1:21:07.154
even when we’re disconnected.

1:21:07.238 --> 1:21:09.031
Okay, so how do we fix it?

1:21:09.115 --> 1:21:11.576
[Isabel] By taking ten blue
crystals each. Liang, let’s go.

1:21:11.659 --> 1:21:13.411
But don’t they have crystals
here in the lab?

1:21:13.494 --> 1:21:14.870
[Isabel]
They don’t exist out here.

1:21:14.954 --> 1:21:16.247
We need to go back.

1:21:16.330 --> 1:21:18.583
They’re only manufactured
inside of there.

1:21:18.666 --> 1:21:19.959
[Liang]
Dr. Clemens, there’s a problem.

1:21:20.042 --> 1:21:21.711
The main brain gamma is low.

1:21:21.794 --> 1:21:23.421
Liang, we’re leaving now!

1:21:23.504 --> 1:21:25.673
[Liang] Well, I can only make it
ride up for a couple seconds.

1:21:25.756 --> 1:21:27.091
[Isabel]
Are you ready?

1:21:27.174 --> 1:21:28.884
[Liang] Dr. Clemens,
what about the study?

1:21:28.968 --> 1:21:30.219
Your mission?

1:21:30.303 --> 1:21:33.306
Shut the fuck up
and press the button already!

1:21:33.389 --> 1:21:35.600
We’ll deal with it later.

1:21:35.683 --> 1:21:37.268
[whooshing]

1:21:37.351 --> 1:21:39.562
[sirens wailing in distance]

1:21:49.739 --> 1:21:51.866
♪ ♪

1:21:59.123 --> 1:22:00.541
Baby!

1:22:00.625 --> 1:22:02.043
Baby, we’re back in.

1:22:02.126 --> 1:22:03.628
Come on.

1:22:03.711 --> 1:22:05.880
Let’s go find Kendo.

1:22:15.473 --> 1:22:16.724
Kendo here?

1:22:16.807 --> 1:22:19.018
-You’re not allowed in here.
-Zip it.

1:22:20.227 --> 1:22:22.313
[sighs]
All right, you fake fucks.

1:22:22.396 --> 1:22:24.607
Where’s Kendo? We need 20 blues.

1:22:24.690 --> 1:22:26.859
-No one’s got blues.
-Kendo will.

1:22:26.942 --> 1:22:28.194
Where is he? Hmm?

1:22:28.277 --> 1:22:30.404
-Where is he?
-[Greg] Hey, hey. Whoa, whoa.

1:22:31.572 --> 1:22:32.907
Let’s start again.

1:22:32.990 --> 1:22:35.576
Where is Kendo? Hmm?

1:22:38.537 --> 1:22:39.872
Where is he?

1:22:44.585 --> 1:22:46.003
Hey.

1:22:46.087 --> 1:22:48.255
What are you doing alive?
Hey, Bjorn!

1:22:48.339 --> 1:22:49.632
-Someone call security.
-Okay.

1:22:49.715 --> 1:22:50.925
I’m gonna get it. Guys!

1:22:51.008 --> 1:22:52.385
I saw you fall out the window.

1:22:52.468 --> 1:22:54.220
He jumped out the window!
You saw it, too!

1:22:54.303 --> 1:22:55.638
He fell right over there,

1:22:55.721 --> 1:22:57.056
-right out that window!
-Should I, should I call...

1:22:57.139 --> 1:22:58.391
-Bjorn, look at me.
-I’m out of here.

1:22:58.474 --> 1:22:59.642
Look at me.
No, no, I’m calm. I’m calm.

1:22:59.725 --> 1:23:00.851
-Do you want me to call her?
-You saw him.

1:23:00.935 --> 1:23:02.603
-Greg, get some food.
-What are you doing?

1:23:02.687 --> 1:23:04.105
Don’t do that to me!

1:23:04.188 --> 1:23:06.774
-Come on, come on, come on...
-No, no. Just tell me why!

1:23:06.857 --> 1:23:07.733
-Here...
-Now! Now! Move!

1:23:07.817 --> 1:23:09.610
Let’s go! Come on!

1:23:09.694 --> 1:23:11.195
I found Kendo.

1:23:11.278 --> 1:23:12.321
Bjorn’s alive.

1:23:12.405 --> 1:23:13.531
My boss is alive.

1:23:13.614 --> 1:23:15.324
-Did you see that?
-Oh, my God.

1:23:15.408 --> 1:23:17.660
That’s an FGP.

1:23:17.743 --> 1:23:20.204
They rebooted him! Come on.

1:23:20.287 --> 1:23:22.289
[Greg]
Kendo’s at Doc Henry’s?

1:23:22.373 --> 1:23:24.125
[Isabel]
No, but our car is.

1:23:24.208 --> 1:23:26.335
[Greg]
Fake, fake, fake!

1:23:27.837 --> 1:23:30.673
Hello, beauties.

1:23:30.756 --> 1:23:33.759
Has anybody got some Tabasco?

1:23:33.843 --> 1:23:37.012
Tabasco? Bitch, what the fuck
you talking about?

1:23:37.096 --> 1:23:38.222
Mace.

1:23:38.305 --> 1:23:39.765
For the bad boys.

1:23:39.849 --> 1:23:41.809
Get out of here
with your fucked-up teeth.

1:23:41.892 --> 1:23:44.186
[laughter]

1:23:44.270 --> 1:23:46.689
Give this bitch a toothbrush.

1:23:46.772 --> 1:23:49.400
Yeah, I got fucked-up teeth,
but I also got a 20.

1:23:49.483 --> 1:23:51.527
Give it to me. Who has it?

1:23:52.987 --> 1:23:54.488
[sighs]

1:23:55.531 --> 1:23:57.074
Fake, fake, fake, fake!

1:23:57.158 --> 1:23:59.368
Real!

1:24:01.495 --> 1:24:05.124
[woman]
Hey, blondie, two for one.

1:24:05.207 --> 1:24:06.959
Hey.

1:24:07.042 --> 1:24:08.377
You in the mood?

1:24:08.461 --> 1:24:10.379
It’s the only reason
I come to this shithole.

1:24:11.589 --> 1:24:13.007
[Isabel taps car roof]

1:24:15.384 --> 1:24:17.094
[man chuckles]

1:24:17.178 --> 1:24:19.972
So, what is it gonna be?

1:24:20.055 --> 1:24:23.476
Uh, let’s have a BJ
and a finger in the butt.

1:24:23.559 --> 1:24:25.144
-Sure.
-[chuckling] All right.

1:24:25.227 --> 1:24:27.521
-Let me get my lipstick.
-All right.

1:24:27.605 --> 1:24:30.107
-[man screaming]
-[Isabel yelling]

1:24:32.902 --> 1:24:35.529
[grunting]

1:24:37.782 --> 1:24:39.784
No, no, the wallet! The wallet!

1:24:41.577 --> 1:24:43.662
Yes! Blues!

1:24:43.746 --> 1:24:45.873
-Here we go!
-[engine starts]

1:24:45.956 --> 1:24:47.750
Look what I found.

1:24:49.418 --> 1:24:50.920
-[Isabel yells]
-[tires squeal]

1:24:51.003 --> 1:24:52.379
[Isabel]
Yes!

1:24:52.463 --> 1:24:54.715
[Isabel shouting in Spanish]

1:24:58.135 --> 1:25:00.221
♪ ♪

1:25:00.304 --> 1:25:01.722
[tires screech]

1:25:04.391 --> 1:25:05.935
Okay, philosophical question:

1:25:06.018 --> 1:25:08.020
Kendo’s real,
so if Kendo... if he...

1:25:08.103 --> 1:25:09.522
Yeah, Kendo is real,

1:25:09.605 --> 1:25:12.691
but if he dies here,
he doesn’t die out there.

1:25:12.775 --> 1:25:14.401
I’m not gonna do
anything to him.

1:25:14.485 --> 1:25:15.861
Stop looking at me that way.

1:25:18.030 --> 1:25:19.657
Dr. Clemens.

1:25:19.740 --> 1:25:22.701
Kendo, we need blue crystals.

1:25:22.785 --> 1:25:24.370
I don’t have time
to explain it to you,

1:25:24.453 --> 1:25:26.288
but shit’s falling apart
one level up.

1:25:26.372 --> 1:25:27.790
-Give them to me. Go get them!
-Okay.

1:25:27.873 --> 1:25:29.166
Okay, sure, you got it.

1:25:29.250 --> 1:25:30.209
Go get them!

1:25:30.292 --> 1:25:31.669
-Now!
-Okay.

1:25:31.752 --> 1:25:34.296
I have them on me, right here...

1:25:34.380 --> 1:25:36.006
Ah, fuck!

1:25:36.090 --> 1:25:38.467
Dr. Clemens, what are you doing?

1:25:42.054 --> 1:25:44.932
-Hey. Hey!
-I thought he went for a gun,

1:25:45.015 --> 1:25:47.017
but he actually did have them.

1:25:47.101 --> 1:25:49.395
-Sorry, Kendo.
-Sorry?

1:25:49.478 --> 1:25:51.146
I mean, it starts to feel like

1:25:51.230 --> 1:25:53.399
you’re making this up
as you go along, that...

1:25:53.482 --> 1:25:54.900
He’s fine.

1:25:54.984 --> 1:25:57.403
Maybe just a mild stomachache,
but he’s fine.

1:25:57.486 --> 1:25:58.988
-[sirens blaring]
-[shouting outside]

1:25:59.071 --> 1:26:00.531
[officer]
Police!

1:26:00.614 --> 1:26:01.907
-[Greg] Go!
-Hold it!

1:26:01.991 --> 1:26:03.117
-Stay where you are!
-[Isabel] Go this way!

1:26:03.200 --> 1:26:04.910
[officer]
Stop!

1:26:04.994 --> 1:26:06.453
This is fake.

1:26:06.537 --> 1:26:08.080
-This is fake. This is fake.
-[sirens wailing]

1:26:08.163 --> 1:26:09.623
Come on, can’t you run faster?

1:26:09.707 --> 1:26:11.041
[Isabel]
This is way too much running.

1:26:11.125 --> 1:26:12.668
[Greg] Can’t we just take
the blues here?

1:26:12.751 --> 1:26:14.336
[Isabel]
No, we need to get the device

1:26:14.420 --> 1:26:15.629
to take it through the nose.

1:26:15.713 --> 1:26:17.256
We need to get to the tarp home.

1:26:17.339 --> 1:26:18.507
[Greg]
Why didn’t we get it

1:26:18.591 --> 1:26:19.925
before we started
shooting people?

1:26:20.009 --> 1:26:22.219
[Isabel mock whining]

1:26:26.181 --> 1:26:27.516
[Greg]
Hurry, hurry, hurry, hurry.

1:26:36.942 --> 1:26:38.652
[Arthur]
Okay, okay.

1:26:38.736 --> 1:26:40.070
I got a call.

1:26:40.154 --> 1:26:42.531
He was panhandling
outside of his old office.

1:26:42.615 --> 1:26:44.366
Will you come with me, please?

1:26:44.450 --> 1:26:46.285
I need you.

1:26:57.630 --> 1:26:59.590
[siren wailing in distance]

1:27:04.511 --> 1:27:06.221
[Isabel]
We need to take ten each.

1:27:11.185 --> 1:27:12.394
There’s not enough!

1:27:12.478 --> 1:27:13.687
[Greg]
What do you mean?

1:27:13.771 --> 1:27:14.855
-There’s not enough!
-Count ’em again.

1:27:14.939 --> 1:27:16.231
There’s not enough!

1:27:16.315 --> 1:27:18.067
-Come out with your hands up.
-What?

1:27:18.150 --> 1:27:20.402
We’re so fucked!

1:27:20.486 --> 1:27:21.946
Oh, my God.

1:27:22.029 --> 1:27:23.405
[Greg]
Okay, what does it mean?

1:27:23.489 --> 1:27:25.157
-We’re fucked.
-Yeah, what does it mean?

1:27:25.240 --> 1:27:26.742
We’re so fucked.

1:27:26.825 --> 1:27:28.786
It means that one of us
gets to go home

1:27:28.869 --> 1:27:31.664
-and the other one gets stuck
in this place. -Why? No, no.

1:27:31.747 --> 1:27:33.290
-I’m not staying here.
-We go to...

1:27:33.374 --> 1:27:35.042
-to jail and-and...
-No. No, no, no, no.

1:27:35.125 --> 1:27:36.335
-...for good.
-Listen to me.

1:27:36.418 --> 1:27:38.045
I have to go.

1:27:38.128 --> 1:27:40.422
Okay? I can’t stay here.

1:27:40.506 --> 1:27:42.383
[sighs heavily]

1:27:43.425 --> 1:27:45.511
Don’t worry. It’s okay.

1:27:45.594 --> 1:27:46.971
It’s okay.

1:27:47.054 --> 1:27:49.598
[officer]
We see you behind the tree.

1:27:53.394 --> 1:27:55.604
♪ ♪

1:28:00.609 --> 1:28:02.403
-You-you take it.
-Okay.

1:28:02.486 --> 1:28:04.321
And you’re gonna be okay, right?

1:28:04.405 --> 1:28:05.364
Okay.

1:28:06.573 --> 1:28:08.367
I’m gonna...

1:28:11.286 --> 1:28:13.288
-Maybe we can split it.
-Go, go.

1:28:13.372 --> 1:28:15.165
No, no, it won’t work.

1:28:15.249 --> 1:28:16.709
Go, go. Come on.

1:28:18.252 --> 1:28:20.587
I have an idea.

1:28:20.671 --> 1:28:22.214
What if you kill me?

1:28:25.134 --> 1:28:27.177
Yeah. Look.

1:28:27.261 --> 1:28:28.595
Take this.

1:28:28.679 --> 1:28:33.851
Just crush my skull,
and then I meet you back there.

1:28:33.934 --> 1:28:36.103
-I’m not staying here.
-That’s bullshit.

1:28:36.186 --> 1:28:37.604
I’m not gonna do that.

1:28:37.688 --> 1:28:39.106
-Why?
-What if it doesn’t work?

1:28:39.189 --> 1:28:40.941
What about Kendo?

1:28:41.025 --> 1:28:42.943
Maybe I killed him.
I don’t know.

1:28:43.027 --> 1:28:45.362
I-I don’t... I don’t know
what to believe.

1:28:45.446 --> 1:28:47.698
Oh, shit.

1:28:47.781 --> 1:28:48.949
Fuck.

1:28:49.033 --> 1:28:50.826
We’re fucking surrounded?

1:28:50.909 --> 1:28:52.953
[officer] Down there!
Get your men down there!

1:28:53.037 --> 1:28:54.204
[officer]
Let’s go!

1:28:54.288 --> 1:28:55.748
[crying]
We’re in a pickle.

1:28:55.831 --> 1:28:57.332
We’re in a pickle, baby.

1:28:57.416 --> 1:28:58.834
Yeah, we’re in a pickle.

1:29:00.252 --> 1:29:02.004
[Emily]
Okay. Let’s go.

1:29:07.551 --> 1:29:08.927
You’re not coming?

1:29:09.011 --> 1:29:11.430
I’m-a be right here.

1:29:11.513 --> 1:29:13.182
I’m here for you.

1:29:13.265 --> 1:29:14.433
Thank you.

1:29:14.516 --> 1:29:17.478
[helicopter whirring overhead]

1:29:21.774 --> 1:29:23.525
Fuck!

1:29:23.609 --> 1:29:25.194
[panting]

1:29:25.277 --> 1:29:27.571
Shit.

1:29:27.654 --> 1:29:29.239
This is horrible.

1:29:29.323 --> 1:29:33.160
This is... this is
a fucking nightmare.

1:29:37.039 --> 1:29:39.124
It’s my fault.

1:29:39.208 --> 1:29:40.417
I created this.

1:29:40.501 --> 1:29:42.252
I created this shit.

1:29:42.336 --> 1:29:43.337
Just me.

1:29:43.420 --> 1:29:45.714
♪ ♪

1:29:48.258 --> 1:29:49.676
[Isabel crying softly]

1:30:03.774 --> 1:30:06.068
♪ ♪

1:30:12.574 --> 1:30:15.244
But it’s also kind of beautiful.

1:30:18.163 --> 1:30:19.915
It is.

1:30:19.998 --> 1:30:22.501
Look, I mean,
even with the cops coming

1:30:22.584 --> 1:30:24.169
and with us running and just...

1:30:24.253 --> 1:30:27.131
You know, everyone’s playing
their part, and we’re all...

1:30:27.214 --> 1:30:29.007
like, we never know
how it’s gonna end.

1:30:29.091 --> 1:30:31.218
One minute, we’re
roller-skating and laughing.

1:30:31.301 --> 1:30:32.845
Remember?

1:30:32.928 --> 1:30:35.305
Yeah, and then the next minute,
can’t even afford a sandwich,

1:30:35.389 --> 1:30:37.099
and then the next minute,
you never know.

1:30:37.182 --> 1:30:39.601
That’s what I love about here
and what you created.

1:30:39.685 --> 1:30:42.146
You don’t know
what’s gonna happen.

1:30:42.229 --> 1:30:44.273
It’s fucked-up.

1:30:44.356 --> 1:30:46.191
And it’s great.

1:30:46.275 --> 1:30:48.360
And I’m not leaving.

1:30:52.781 --> 1:30:54.491
I’m not leaving.

1:30:55.534 --> 1:30:57.494
Dad!

1:30:58.579 --> 1:31:00.247
Dad!

1:31:02.916 --> 1:31:04.668
Dad!

1:31:06.086 --> 1:31:08.046
[officer] Keep an eye out!
Stay back! Stay back!

1:31:08.130 --> 1:31:09.882
-No! No, no, no! Please wait!
No, wait! -Come on, go.

1:31:09.965 --> 1:31:11.800
-Get in the car.
-Wait! Wait!

1:31:16.180 --> 1:31:17.598
Dad!

1:31:18.932 --> 1:31:21.226
[helicopter whirring overhead]

1:31:30.527 --> 1:31:32.779
[Isabel sighs]

1:31:42.331 --> 1:31:44.583
I’m sorry.

1:31:51.715 --> 1:31:54.134
[Isabel]
She’s beautiful.

1:32:03.518 --> 1:32:05.687
♪ ♪

1:32:17.616 --> 1:32:19.034
Go.

1:32:20.202 --> 1:32:21.870
Hey!

1:32:21.954 --> 1:32:24.081
Come on, motherfuckers!

1:32:24.164 --> 1:32:26.375
Let’s go!

1:32:35.884 --> 1:32:39.054
Drop what’s in your hand.
Ma’am, show what’s in your hand.

1:32:39.137 --> 1:32:41.348
Hands in the air.
Let me see your hands.

1:32:48.480 --> 1:32:50.232
[deep whoosh]

1:32:51.066 --> 1:32:53.151
[train horn blaring]

1:32:53.235 --> 1:32:54.486
[footsteps running]

1:33:00.200 --> 1:33:02.494
[train horn continues blaring]

1:33:13.922 --> 1:33:16.174
[sirens wailing in distance]

1:33:31.606 --> 1:33:33.775
[sirens wailing]

1:33:58.884 --> 1:34:01.011
[panting]

1:34:12.606 --> 1:34:14.900
♪ ♪

1:34:25.577 --> 1:34:27.746
♪ ♪

1:34:50.936 --> 1:34:53.230
♪ ♪

1:35:18.088 --> 1:35:20.257
♪ ♪

1:35:39.359 --> 1:35:41.903
This is, uh, Greg’s first time.

1:35:41.987 --> 1:35:44.239
Welcome, Greg.

1:35:44.322 --> 1:35:47.909
In this house, there’s no stigma
for what you’re going through.

1:35:47.993 --> 1:35:50.829
Every person on this planet
can relate

1:35:50.912 --> 1:35:54.291
to wanting to chase bliss.

1:35:54.374 --> 1:35:59.004
It’s an open forum, so you can
say anything you want.

1:35:59.087 --> 1:36:01.298
We’re here to listen.

1:36:13.101 --> 1:36:16.605
[takes deep, trembling breath]

1:36:51.515 --> 1:36:54.684
This woman says
she’s my daughter.

1:36:56.811 --> 1:36:59.022
And I believe her.

1:37:08.573 --> 1:37:10.742
♪ ♪

1:37:28.468 --> 1:37:30.637
♪ ♪

1:37:45.193 --> 1:37:47.404
[footsteps approaching]

1:37:57.581 --> 1:37:59.165
Hi, Dad.

1:38:01.334 --> 1:38:03.545
Sorry I’m late. I...

1:38:04.921 --> 1:38:08.967
I saw these flowers
on the side of the road.

1:38:09.050 --> 1:38:11.803
I thought they looked nice,
I guess.

1:38:12.721 --> 1:38:14.848
[chuckles]

1:38:16.224 --> 1:38:18.101
You’re not late, Dad.

1:38:21.688 --> 1:38:23.690
You’re here.

1:38:43.501 --> 1:38:45.337
[waves lapping]

1:38:45.420 --> 1:38:48.798
